{"title_page": "Abid Ali (actor)", "text_new": "{{Use Pakistani English|date=June 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Abid Ali\n| image              = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = Abid Sher Ali\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1952|3|29|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Quetta]], [[Pakistan]]\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2019|9|5|1952|3|29|df=yes}}<ref name=\"khaleejtimes\">https://www.khaleejtimes.com/international/pakistan/veteran-pakistani-actor-abid-ali-passes-away</ref>\n| death_place        = [[Karachi]], [[Pakistan]]\n| nationality        = [[Pakistan]]\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n*Actor\n*Director\n*Producer\n}}\n| years_active       = 1973\u20132019\n| known_for          = [[Waris (serial)|Waris]]\n| notable_works      = \n| awards             = [[Pride of Performance]] Award by the [[President of Pakistan]] in 1985\n| spouse             = Humaira Ali (divorced) <br/> [[Rabia Noreen]] (-2019 his death);\n| parents            = \n| relatives          = [[Iman Ali]] (daughter) <br/> Rahma Ali (daughter) <br/> Mariyam Ali (daughter)\n           <br/> Muhammad Rashid Now from Daska , Sialkot working as Teacher At Galotian High School. (Son)\n}}\n'''Abid Sher Ali''' (29 March 1952 \u2013 5 September 2019)<ref name=\"khaleejtimes\"/> was a [[Pakistani]] [[actor]], director and producer. Ali acted in numerous television dramas and films but is best known for his role as '''Dilawar Khan''' in the [[Pakistan_Television_Corporation|PTV's]] classic drama ''[[Waris (drama)|Waris]]'' (1979).<ref name=Tribune/>\n\n==Family==\nHe was married twice. From his former marriage to actress and singer Humaira Ali (n\u00e9e Chaudhry),<ref name=BR>Khushbakht Shahid  (21 April 2018), [https://www.brecorder.com/2018/04/21/413357/pakistani-mother-daughter-celebrities-who-were-too-good-to-be-ignored/ \"Pakistani mother-daughter celebrities who were too good to be ignored\"] ''The Business Recorder'' (newspaper), Retrieved 3 June 2019.</ref> he had three daughters and a son (Muhammad Rashid) including the supermodel-turned-actress [[Iman Ali]] as well as the actress and singer Rahma Ali.<ref>Mehek Saeed (7 March 2015), Muhammad Rashid working as a teacher in District Sialkot. [https://tribune.com.pk/story/849500/1-rahma-alis-gaari-moving-forward-halke-halke/ \"Rahma Ali\u2019s gaari moving forward halke halke\"] ''The Express Tribune'' (newspaper), Retrieved 3 June 2019.</ref><ref name=BR/>\n\n==Early life and career==\nBorn and educated in [[Quetta]], Abid Ali was attracted to the arts from early age, writing stories and painting in his childhood and teenage years, and first entered [[Radio Pakistan]] before going to [[Lahore]] after some struggle and launching his successful TV career with PTV's drama serial ''Jhok Sial'' in 1973.<ref name=Tribune>Saadia Qamar (22 December 2011), [https://tribune.com.pk/story/310447/tete-a-tete-with-abid-ali/ \"Tete-a-tete with Abid Ali\"] ''The Express Tribune'' (newspaper), Retrieved 3 June 2019</ref> \n\nHe launched himself as a director and producer with the 1993-hit drama ''[[Dasht (TV series)|Dasht]]'', also the first private production for Pakistan, while the same year, for [[Pakistan Television Corporation|PTV]] this time, he directed the drama ''Doosra Aasman'', the first drama shot abroad, followed by other projects for many channels, including  ''Saheli'' in 2007, or ''Massi aur Malka'', a family based-drama, in 2009, usually acting in these serials as well.\n\n== Illness and death ==\nAli was hospitalized on 2 September 2019 at [[Liaquat National Hospital]] in [[Karachi]].<ref name=\"The News\">{{cite news |title=Veteran actor Abid Ali hospitalized over severe health condition |url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/521058 |work=The News International |date=September 2, 2019}}</ref> He died on 5 September 2019 due to liver failure while in the hospital, aged 67.<ref name=\"khaleejtimes\"/> He was laid to rest on 6 September 2019 after his funeral prayers were held at Masjid-e-Aashiq in [[Bahria Town Karachi|Bahria Town, Karachi]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Acting legend Abid Ali laid to rest in Karachi |url=https://www.samaa.tv/news/2019/09/acting-legend-abid-ali-laid-to-rest-in-karachi/ |work=Samaa TV |date=September 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Eminent actor Abid Ali laid to rest |url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1503961/ |work=Dawn |date=September 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and recognition==\n*[[Pride of Performance]] Award by the [[President of Pakistan]] in 1985.<ref name=Urdubiography/>\n\n==Selected television==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year!!Title!!Role!!Channel !! Notes \n|-\n|1973 ||''[[Jhok Sial]]'' || || [[PTV Home]] || debut role\n|-\n|1978\u201379 ||''[[Waris (drama)|Waris]]''<ref name=Tribune/> || Dilawar Khan||[[PTV Home]]|| \n|-\n|1983 ||''[[Sumandar]]'' || || [[PTV Home]]|| \n|-\n|1984 ||''[[Ana (TV series)|Aan]]'' || || [[PTV Home]]|| \n|-\n|1986||''[[Waqt (TV series)|Waqt]]''|| ||[[PTV Home]]||\n|-\n|1987 ||''Piyaas''||  ||[[PTV Home]]|| \n|-\n|1989||''[[Khwahish]]''|| ||[[PTV Home]]||\n|-\n| 1991||''[[Dooriyan]]''||  ||[[Network Television Marketing]]|| \n|-\n|1993||''[[Dasht (TV series)|Dasht]]''<ref name=\"Urdubiography\" />||  || [[Network Television Marketing]]|| \n|-\n|2003 ||''[[Mehndi (drama)|Mehndi]]''|| Ali Hassan ||[[PTV Home]] || \n|-\n|2004 ||''[[Patal (TV series)|Patal]]''|| ||[[PTV Home]]|| \n|-\n|2004 ||''[[Moorat]]''||Eunuch Reshma ||[[ARY Digital]]|| \n|-\n|2005 ||''[[Naseeb (TV series)|Naseeb]]''|| ||[[PTV Home]]|| \n|-\n|2005 ||''[[Matti (TV series)|Matti]]''|| ||[[PTV Home]]|| \n|-\n|2005 ||''[[Mar Jayen Hum Tu Kiya]]''|| ||[[ATV (Pakistan)]]|| \n|-\n|2013 ||''[[Bunty I Love You]]''<ref name=\"Instep\">{{cite news |title=Legendary actor Abid Ali is no more |url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/magazine/instep-today/523214-legendary-actor-abid-ali-is-no-more |work=The News}