man_Emperor"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Mexico", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing pandemic in New Mexico, United States}}\n{{Current event|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Mexico\n| map1            = File:COVID-19_Cases_in_New_Mexico_by_counties.svg\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| legend1         = Map of the outbreak in New Mexico (as of 19 March)\n{{legend|#FFDDCC|1\u20134 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FFAAAA|5\u20139 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FF7777|10\u201324 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FF0000|25\u201349 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#BB0000|50\u2013100 confirmed}}\n| location        = [[New Mexico]], [[United States]]\n| first_case      = [[Socorro County, New Mexico|Socorro County]], [[Bernalillo County, New Mexico|Bernalillo County]]\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| arrival_date    = March 11, 2020\n| confirmed_cases = 315\n\n| recovery_cases  = 26\n| deaths          = 5\n| website         = {{URL|https://cv.nmhealth.org/}}\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]<br>(Global)\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[New Mexico]] in March 11, 2020.\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/New Mexico medical cases chart}}\n\n* '''March 11:''' The initial three cases of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] in [[New Mexico]] were reported on by the [[New Mexico Department of Health]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/11/new-mexico-announces-first-presumptive-positive-covid-19-cases/|title=New Mexico Announces First Presumptive Positive COVID-19 Cases|last=|first=|date=2020-03-11|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> They included a couple in their 60s in [[Socorro County, New Mexico|Socorro County]] with a travel history to [[Egypt]] and a woman in her 70s in [[Bernalillo County, New Mexico|Bernalillo County]] with a travel history to the [[New York City]] area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/11/new-mexico-announces-another-positive-covid-19-case/|title=New Mexico Announces Another Positive COVID-19 Case|last=|first=|date=2020-03-11|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> The same day, an additional case was announced: a [[Santa Fe County, New Mexico|Santa Fe County]] woman in her 70s, also with a New York City area travel history. Governor [[Michelle Lujan Grisham]] and the Department of Health cautioned against large gatherings and non-essential travel outside of New Mexico. As a result of the cases, Lujan Grisham signed Executive Order 2020\u2013004, declaring a statewide [[Public health emergency (United States)|public health emergency]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Executive-Order-2020-004.pdf|title=Executive Order 2020-004|last=|first=|date=2020-03-11|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n* '''March 12:''' Two more cases were confirmed. These were a Bernalillo County man in his 40s<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/12/new-mexico-announces-fifth-presumptive-positive-covid-19-case/|title=New Mexico Announces Fifth Presumptive Positive COVID-19 Case|last=|first=|date=2020-03-12|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> and a Santa Fe County woman in her 50s who had travelled to [[Italy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/12/new-mexico-announces-sixth-presumptive-positive-covid-19-case/|title=New Mexico Announces Sixth Presumptive Positive COVID-19 Case|last=|first=|date=2020-03-12|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n* '''March 13:''' Four more cases were confirmed. These included Bernalillo County men in their 50s and 80s and a Bernalillo County woman in her 70s, all with contact to previously diagnosed patients, as well as a Santa Fe County woman in her 20s who had travelled to [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/13/new-mexico-announces-four-more-positive-covid-19-cases/|title=New Mexico Announces Four More Positive COVID-19 Cases|last=|first=|date=2020-03-13|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n* '''March 14:''' Three more cases were confirmed. The patients included one [[Sandoval County, New Mexico|Sandoval County]] man and one woman, both in their 60s, and a Bernalillo county woman in her 50s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/14/update-on-new-mexico-covid-19-cases/|title=Update on New Mexico COVID-19 Cases|last=|first=|date=2020-03-14|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n* '''March 15:''' Four more cases were confirmed. The new patients were all men from Bernalillo County: one each in their 20s and 40s, and two in their 30s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/15/update-on-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-2/|title=Update on New Mexico COVID-19 cases|last=|first=|date=2020-03-15|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n* '''March 16:''' Four more cases were confirmed. They were all from Bernalillo County: one man in his 20s, two women in their 30s, and one man in his 80s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/16/update-on-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-3/|title=Update on New Mexico COVID-19 cases|last=|first=|date=2020-03-16|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n* '''March 17:''' Two more cases were confirmed. Two men were diagnosed, one in his 40s in Santa Fe County and one in his 50s in [[Taos County, New Mexico|Taos County]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/17/update-on-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-23/|title=Update on New Mexico COVID-19 cases: Now at 23|last=|first=|date=2020-03-17|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n* '''March 18:''' Five more cases were confirmed. They included a woman in her 40s in Bernalillo County, a woman in her 80s in Bernalillo County, a woman in her 30s in Santa Fe County, a woman in her teens in Sandoval County, and a woman in her 50s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/18/update-on-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-28/|title=Update on New Mexico COVID-19 cases: Now at 28|last=|first=|date=2020-03-18|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> The case of the Bernalillo County woman in her 40s was under investigation as potential community spread, with no known travel or personal link.\n* '''March 19:''' Seven more cases were confirmed. Four cases were from Bernalillo County, two from Santa Fe County, and one from [[San Miguel County, New Mexico|San Miguel County]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/19/update-on-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-35/|title=Update on New Mexico COVID-19 cases: Now at 35|last=|first=|date=2020-03-19|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> The Department of Health noted for the first time that it had detected community spread within New Mexico.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n*'''March 20:''' An additional eight cases were confirmed, including the first cases in [[Do\u00f1a Ana County, New Mexico|Do\u00f1a Ana]] and [[McKinley County, New Mexico|McKinley]] counties. Two more cases each of Bernalillo and Sandoval counties, as well as a new case in Taos County, were also confirmed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/20/updated-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-43/|title=Updated New Mexico COVID-19 cases: Now at 43|last=|first=|date=2020-03-20|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n*'''March 21''': 14 new cases were confirmed, including the first case in [[Lea County, New Mexico|Lea County]]. The other cases confirmed consisted of 9 in Bernalillo County and one each in Do\u00f1a Ana, Sandoval, Santa Fe, and Taos County.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/21/updated-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-57/|title=Updated New Mexico COVID-19 Cases: Now at 57|last=|first=|date=2020-03-21|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n*'''March 22''': Statewide case total is 65 with two new cases in Bernalillo, Do\u00f1a Ana, and Santa Fe counties and one in McKinley and San Juan counties.<ref>https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/22/updated-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-65/</ref>\n*'''March 23''': Governor Grisham announced a statewide [[stay-at-home order]] that requires 100% of non-essential business workforce to work from home effective March 24.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Parker |first1=Jim |title=New Mexico's governor issues stay-at-home order due to coronavirus outbreak |url=https://kvia.com/news/new-mexico/2020/03/23/new-mexicos-governor-to-issue-stay-at-home-order-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=KVIA |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> 18 new cases are also announced with four new cases in Bernalillo and Chaves counties (it was later revealed that one of the Chaves county cases was the result of a clerical error<ref>https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/25/updated-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-112/</ref>), six in Do\u00f1a Ana and two in San Juan and Santa Fe counties bringing the reported statewide total to 83.<ref>https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/23/updated-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-83/</ref>\n*'''March 24''': Total cases reach 100 as 17 new cases are reported with five new cases in Bernalillo county, three in Do\u00f1a Ana, four in San Juan, two in Santa Fe, and one in McKinley as well as Cibola and Curry the first for those counties.<ref>https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/24/updated-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-100/</ref>\n*'''March 25''': The first death in the state is reported. A male in his late 70s died on March 22 at Artesia General Hospital. A COVID-19 test was done and confirmed late on March 24 that he tested positive for the virus. The individual also had multiple underlying chronic health issues.<ref>https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/25/new-mexico-covid-19-update-one-death/</ref> 13 new cases are reported with five in Bernalillo county, three in Santa Fe, two in Rio Arriba, one in San Juan and Sandoval counties and a deceased male in Eddy County bringing the statewide total to 112.<ref>https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/25/updated-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-112/</ref>\n*'''March 26''': 24 more cases are reported with seven new cases in Bernalillo county, six in San Juan, five in Santa Fe, three in Do\u00f1a Ana, two in Sandoval, and one in Chaves county bringing the statewide total to 136.<ref>https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/26/updated-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-136/</ref>\n*'''March 27''': Total cases reach 191 as 55 more cases are reported with 27 in Bernalillo county, 7 in Santa Fe, 5 in Sandoval and Taos, 3 in San Juan, 2 in McKinley, and one in Cibola, Eddy, Lea, Rio Arriba, Roosevelt, and Valencia counties.<ref>https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/27/updated-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-191/</ref>\n*'''March 28''': The second death in the state is reported in Bernalillo county, a male in his 80s with chronic health issues died on March 27. 17 more cases are reported with 11 in Bernalillo, 3 in Chaves, and one in Do\u00f1a Ana, Eddy and San Juan counties bringing the statewide total to 208. The New Mexico Department of Health also reports that 26 cases are designated as having recovered.<ref>https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/28/updated-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-208/</ref>\n*'''March 29''': 29 new cases are reported with nine in Bernalillo, four in McKinley, San Juan and Santa Fe counties, three in Sandoval, two in Curry, and one in Chaves and Valencia counties bringing the statewide total to 237.<ref>https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/29/updated-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-237/</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Cases by County\n!County\n!Cases\n!Deaths\n!Recovered\n|-\n|[[Bernalillo County, New Mexico|Bernalillo]]\n|129\n|4\n|0\n|-\n|[[Santa Fe County, New Mexico|Santa Fe]]\n|42\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[San Juan County, New Mexico|San Juan]]\n|32\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Do\u00f1a Ana County, New Mexico|Do\u00f1a Ana]]\n|18\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Sandoval County, New Mexico|Sandoval]]\n|29\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Taos County, New Mexico|Taos County]]\n|11\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[McKinley County, New Mexico|McKinley]]\n|16\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Chaves County, New Mexico|Chaves]]\n|10\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Rio Arriba County, New Mexico|Rio Arriba]]\n|4\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Torrance County, New Mexico|Torrance]]\n|3\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Socorro County, New Mexico|Socorro]]\n|3\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Cibola County, New Mexico|Cibola]]\n|2\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Curry County, New Mexico|Curry]]\n|3\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Eddy County, New Mexico|Eddy]]\n|4\n|1\n|0\n|-\n|[[San Miguel County, New Mexico|San Miguel]]\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Lea County, New Mexico|Lea]]\n|2\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Roosevelt County, New Mexico|Roosevelt]]\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Valencia County, New Mexico|Valencia]]\n|5\n|0\n|0\n|-\n!Total\n!315\n!5\n!26*\n|}\n<nowiki>*</nowiki> The 26 recoveries have not yet been specified by county.\n\n*\n\n==Impact==\n===Schools===\nOn March 12 the governor announced that all public schools in the state would be closed for three weeks beginning at the end of the school day on March 13.<ref>https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/new-mexico/articles/2020-03-12/albuquerque-academy-closes-classrooms-on-covid-19-concerns</ref> On March 27 it was announced that schools would remain closed for the rest of the academic year. New education plans are in development including online or paper packets sent by mail as well as educational programs being developed for PBS stations beginning on April 6. Plans to determine \"demonstrations of competency\" for graduating seniors are also being worked out. Some school teachers will also receive training for new \"distance learning\" programs such as virtual classrooms.<ref>https://www.abqjournal.com/1437299/nm-public-schools-to-stay-closed-for-rest-of-year.html</ref>\n\n===Businesses===\nNon-essential businesses have been ordered to close as of March 24. These include shopping malls, flea markets, movie theaters, gyms and health clubs, hair and nail salons, bars, nightclubs, entertainment venues, casinos and convention centers. Restaurants are open only to take-out orders. This order is in effect until April 10 but could be extended.<ref>https://www.krqe.com/health/coronavirus-resources/faq-what-you-need-to-know-about-the-new-mexico-stay-at-home-order/</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://cv.nmhealth.org/ Coronavirus information] from the [[New Mexico Department of Health]]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|New Mexico]]\n[[Category:2020 in New Mexico|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Health in New Mexico]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Current event|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in New Mexico\n| map1            = File:COVID-19_Cases_in_New_Mexico_by_counties.svg\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| legend1         = Map of the outbreak in New Mexico (as of 19 March)\n{{legend|#FFDDCC|1\u20134 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FFAAAA|5\u20139 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FF7777|10\u201324 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#FF0000|25\u201349 confirmed}}\n{{legend|#BB0000|50\u2013100 confirmed}}\n| location        = [[New Mexico]], [[United States]]\n| first_case      = [[Socorro County, New Mexico|Socorro County]], [[Bernalillo County, New Mexico|Bernalillo County]]\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| arrival_date    = March 11, 2020\n| confirmed_cases = 315\n\n| recovery_cases  = 26\n| deaths          = 5\n| website         = {{URL|https://cv.nmhealth.org/}}\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]<br>(Global)\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[New Mexico]] in March 11, 2020.\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/New Mexico medical cases chart}}\n\n* '''March 11:''' The initial three cases of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] in [[New Mexico]] were reported on by the [[New Mexico Department of Health]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/11/new-mexico-announces-first-presumptive-positive-covid-19-cases/|title=New Mexico Announces First Presumptive Positive COVID-19 Cases|last=|first=|date=2020-03-11|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> They included a couple in their 60s in [[Socorro County, New Mexico|Socorro County]] with a travel history to [[Egypt]] and a woman in her 70s in [[Bernalillo County, New Mexico|Bernalillo County]] with a travel history to the [[New York City]] area.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/11/new-mexico-announces-another-positive-covid-19-case/|title=New Mexico Announces Another Positive COVID-19 Case|last=|first=|date=2020-03-11|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> The same day, an additional case was announced: a [[Santa Fe County, New Mexico|Santa Fe County]] woman in her 70s, also with a New York City area travel history. Governor [[Michelle Lujan Grisham]] and the Department of Health cautioned against large gatherings and non-essential travel outside of New Mexico. As a result of the cases, Lujan Grisham signed Executive Order 2020\u2013004, declaring a statewide [[Public health emergency (United States)|public health emergency]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Executive-Order-2020-004.pdf|title=Executive Order 2020-004|last=|first=|date=2020-03-11|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n* '''March 12:''' Two more cases were confirmed. These were a Bernalillo County man in his 40s<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/12/new-mexico-announces-fifth-presumptive-positive-covid-19-case/|title=New Mexico Announces Fifth Presumptive Positive COVID-19 Case|last=|first=|date=2020-03-12|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> and a Santa Fe County woman in her 50s who had travelled to [[Italy]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/12/new-mexico-announces-sixth-presumptive-positive-covid-19-case/|title=New Mexico Announces Sixth Presumptive Positive COVID-19 Case|last=|first=|date=2020-03-12|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n* '''March 13:''' Four more cases were confirmed. These included Bernalillo County men in their 50s and 80s and a Bernalillo County woman in her 70s, all with contact to previously diagnosed patients, as well as a Santa Fe County woman in her 20s who had travelled to [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/13/new-mexico-announces-four-more-positive-covid-19-cases/|title=New Mexico Announces Four More Positive COVID-19 Cases|last=|first=|date=2020-03-13|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n* '''March 14:''' Three more cases were confirmed. The patients included one [[Sandoval County, New Mexico|Sandoval County]] man and one woman, both in their 60s, and a Bernalillo county woman in her 50s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/14/update-on-new-mexico-covid-19-cases/|title=Update on New Mexico COVID-19 Cases|last=|first=|date=2020-03-14|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n* '''March 15:''' Four more cases were confirmed. The new patients were all men from Bernalillo County: one each in their 20s and 40s, and two in their 30s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/15/update-on-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-2/|title=Update on New Mexico COVID-19 cases|last=|first=|date=2020-03-15|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n* '''March 16:''' Four more cases were confirmed. They were all from Bernalillo County: one man in his 20s, two women in their 30s, and one man in his 80s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/16/update-on-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-3/|title=Update on New Mexico COVID-19 cases|last=|first=|date=2020-03-16|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n* '''March 17:''' Two more cases were confirmed. Two men were diagnosed, one in his 40s in Santa Fe County and one in his 50s in [[Taos County, New Mexico|Taos County]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/17/update-on-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-23/|title=Update on New Mexico COVID-19 cases: Now at 23|last=|first=|date=2020-03-17|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n* '''March 18:''' Five more cases were confirmed. They included a woman in her 40s in Bernalillo County, a woman in her 80s in Bernalillo County, a woman in her 30s in Santa Fe County, a woman in her teens in Sandoval County, and a woman in her 50s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/18/update-on-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-28/|title=Update on New Mexico COVID-19 cases: Now at 28|last=|first=|date=2020-03-18|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> The case of the Bernalillo County woman in her 40s was under investigation as potential community spread, with no known travel or personal link.\n* '''March 19:''' Seven more cases were confirmed. Four cases were from Bernalillo County, two from Santa Fe County, and one from [[San Miguel County, New Mexico|San Miguel County]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/19/update-on-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-35/|title=Update on New Mexico COVID-19 cases: Now at 35|last=|first=|date=2020-03-19|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> The Department of Health noted for the first time that it had detected community spread within New Mexico.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n*'''March 20:''' An additional eight cases were confirmed, including the first cases in [[Do\u00f1a Ana County, New Mexico|Do\u00f1a Ana]] and [[McKinley County, New Mexico|McKinley]] counties. Two more cases each of Bernalillo and Sandoval counties, as well as a new case in Taos County, were also confirmed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/20/updated-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-43/|title=Updated New Mexico COVID-19 cases: Now at 43|last=|first=|date=2020-03-20|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n*'''March 21''': 14 new cases were confirmed, including the first case in [[Lea County, New Mexico|Lea County]]. The other cases confirmed consisted of 9 in Bernalillo County and one each in Do\u00f1a Ana, Sandoval, Santa Fe, and Taos County.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/21/updated-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-57/|title=Updated New Mexico COVID-19 Cases: Now at 57|last=|first=|date=2020-03-21|website=New Mexico Department of Health|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n*'''March 22''': Statewide case total is 65 with two new cases in Bernalillo, Do\u00f1a Ana, and Santa Fe counties and one in McKinley and San Juan counties.<ref>https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/22/updated-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-65/</ref> \n\n*'''March 23''': Governor Grisham announced a statewide [[stay-at-home order]] that requires 100% of non-essential business workforce to work from home effective March 24.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Parker |first1=Jim |title=New Mexico's governor issues stay-at-home order due to coronavirus outbreak |url=https://kvia.com/news/new-mexico/2020/03/23/new-mexicos-governor-to-issue-stay-at-home-order-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |work=KVIA |date=23 March 2020}}</ref> 18 new cases are also announced with four new cases in Bernalillo and Chaves counties (it was later revealed that one of the Chaves county cases was the result of a clerical error<ref>https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/25/updated-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-112/</ref>), six in Do\u00f1a Ana and two in San Juan and Santa Fe counties bringing the reported statewide total to 83.<ref>https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/23/updated-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-83/</ref>\n\n*'''March 24''': Total cases reach 100 as 17 new cases are reported with five new cases in Bernalillo county, three in Do\u00f1a Ana, four in San Juan, two in Santa Fe, and one in McKinley as well as Cibola and Curry the first for those counties.<ref>https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/24/updated-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-100/</ref>\n\n*'''March 25''': The first death in the state is reported. A male in his late 70s died on March 22 at Artesia General Hospital. A COVID-19 test was done and confirmed late on March 24 that he tested positive for the virus. The individual also had multiple underlying chronic health issues.<ref>https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/25/new-mexico-covid-19-update-one-death/</ref> 13 new cases are reported with five in Bernalillo county, three in Santa Fe, two in Rio Arriba, one in San Juan and Sandoval counties and a deceased male in Eddy County bringing the statewide total to 112.<ref>https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/25/updated-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-112/</ref>  \n\n*'''March 26''': 24 more cases are reported with seven new cases in Bernalillo county, six in San Juan, five in Santa Fe, three in Do\u00f1a Ana, two in Sandoval, and one in Chaves county bringing the statewide total to 136.<ref>https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/26/updated-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-136/</ref>\n\n*'''March 27''': Total cases reach 191 as 55 more cases are reported with 27 in Bernalillo county, 7 in Santa Fe, 5 in Sandoval and Taos, 3 in San Juan, 2 in McKinley, and one in Cibola, Eddy, Lea, Rio Arriba, Roosevelt, and Valencia counties.<ref>https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/27/updated-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-191/</ref> \n\n*'''March 28''': The second death in the state is reported in Bernalillo county, a male in his 80s with chronic health issues died on March 27. 17 more cases are reported with 11 in Bernalillo, 3 in Chaves, and one in Do\u00f1a Ana, Eddy and San Juan counties bringing the statewide total to 208. The New Mexico Department of Health also reports that 26 cases are designated as having recovered.<ref>https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/28/updated-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-208/</ref>\n\n*'''March 29''': 29 new cases are reported with nine in Bernalillo, four in McKinley, San Juan and Santa Fe counties, three in Sandoval, two in Curry, and one in Chaves and Valencia counties bringing the statewide total to 237.<ref>https://cv.nmhealth.org/2020/03/29/updated-new-mexico-covid-19-cases-now-at-237/</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Cases by County\n!County\n!Cases\n!Deaths\n!Recovered\n|-\n|[[Bernalillo County, New Mexico|Bernalillo]]\n|129\n|4\n|0\n|-\n|[[Santa Fe County, New Mexico|Santa Fe]]\n|42\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[San Juan County, New Mexico|San Juan]]\n|32\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Do\u00f1a Ana County, New Mexico|Do\u00f1a Ana]]\n|18\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Sandoval County, New Mexico|Sandoval]]\n|29\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Taos County, New Mexico|Taos County]]\n|11\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[McKinley County, New Mexico|McKinley]]\n|16\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Chaves County, New Mexico|Chaves]]\n|10\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Rio Arriba County, New Mexico|Rio Arriba]]\n|4\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Torrance County, New Mexico|Torrance]]\n|3\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Socorro County, New Mexico|Socorro]]\n|3\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Cibola County, New Mexico|Cibola]]\n|2\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Curry County, New Mexico|Curry]]\n|3\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Eddy County, New Mexico|Eddy]]\n|4\n|1\n|0\n|-\n|[[San Miguel County, New Mexico|San Miguel]]\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Lea County, New Mexico|Lea]]\n|2\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Roosevelt County, New Mexico|Roosevelt]]\n|1\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|[[Valencia County, New Mexico|Valencia]]\n|5\n|0\n|0\n|-\n!Total\n!315\n!5\n!26*\n|}\n<nowiki>*</nowiki> The 26 recoveries have not yet been specified by county.\n\n*\n\n==Impact==\n===Schools===\nOn March 12 the governor announced that all public schools in the state would be closed for three weeks beginning at the end of the school day on March 13.<ref>https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/new-mexico/articles/2020-03-12/albuquerque-academy-closes-classrooms-on-covid-19-concerns</ref> On March 27 it was announced that schools would remain closed for the rest of the academic year. New education plans are in development including online or paper packets sent by mail as well as educational programs being developed for PBS stations beginning on April 6. Plans to determine \"demonstrations of competency\" for graduating seniors are also being worked out. Some school teachers will also receive training for new \"distance learning\" programs such as virtual classrooms.<ref>https://www.abqjournal.com/1437299/nm-public-schools-to-stay-closed-for-rest-of-year.html</ref>  \n \n===Businesses===\nNon-essential businesses have been ordered to close as of March 24. These include shopping malls, flea markets, movie theaters, gyms and health clubs, hair and nail salons, bars, nightclubs, entertainment venues, casinos and convention centers. Restaurants are open only to take-out orders. This order is in effect until April 10 but could be extended.<ref>https://www.krqe.com/health/coronavirus-resources/faq-what-you-need-to-know-about-the-new-mexico-stay-at-home-order/</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://cv.nmhealth.org/ Coronavirus information] from the [[New Mexico Department of Health]]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|New Mexico]]\n[[Category:2020 in New Mexico|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Health in New Mexico]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "The Eloquent Peasant", "label": "safe", "comment": "add short description per WP:SHORT DESC", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_New_Mexico"}
{"title_page": "Mark Meadows (North Carolina politician)", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date = December 2019}}\n{{short description|U.S. Representative from North Carolina}}\n{{For|other people with the same name|Mark Meadows (disambiguation){{!}}Mark Meadows}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Mark Meadows\n|image        = Mark Meadows, Official Portrait, 113th Congress.jpg\n|office       = 29th [[White House Chief of Staff]]\n|president    = [[Donald Trump]]\n|term_start   = March 31, 2020\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Mick Mulvaney]] (acting)\n|successor    = \n|office1      = [[Ranking Member]] of the <br>[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Reform|House Oversight Committee]]\n|term_start1  = March 12, 2020\n|term_end1    = March 30, 2020\n|predecessor1 = [[Jim Jordan (American politician)|Jim Jordan]]\n|successor1   = ''Vacant''\n|office2      = Chair of the House [[Freedom Caucus]]\n|term_start2  = January 3, 2017\n|term_end2    = October 1, 2019\n|predecessor2 = [[Jim Jordan (American politician)|Jim Jordan]]\n|successor2   = [[Andy Biggs]]\n|state3       = [[North Carolina]]\n|district3    = {{ushr|NC|11|11th}}\n|term_start3  = January 3, 2013\n|term_end3    = March 30, 2020\n|predecessor3 = [[Heath Shuler]]\n|successor3   = ''Vacant''\n|birth_name   = Mark Randall Meadows\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1959|7|28}}\n|birth_place  = [[Verdun]], [[France]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|Debbie Meadows|1979}}\n|children     = 2\n|father       = John Robie Meadows\n|education    = [[Florida State University]]<br>([[No Degree|No Degree]])<br>[[University of South Florida]] ([[Associate degree|AA]])\n|website      =    \n}}\n{{Conservatism in the United States}}\n'''Mark Randall Meadows''' (born July 28, 1959) is an American politician who is the 29th and current White House chief of staff. Meadows served as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. representative]] for [[North Carolina's 11th congressional district]] from 2013 to 2020. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] and chaired the [[Freedom Caucus]] from 2017 to 2019. He was considered one of Trump's closest allies in [[United States Congress|Congress]] before his appointment as chief of staff.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/12/10/mark-meadows-trump-white-house-chief-of-staff-1054790|title=Meadows would give Trump a skilled brawler in the White House|publisher=[[Politico]]|date=December 10, 2018|first1=Rachael|last1=Bade|first2=Kyle|last2=Cheney|first3=Eliana|last3=Johnson}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and business career==\nMeadows was born at a [[United States Army]] hospital in [[Verdun]], France, where his father was serving in the Army and his mother worked as a civilian nurse. His mother was from [[Sevierville, Tennessee]], and his father from [[Pineville, Arkansas]].\n\nHe grew up in [[Brandon, Florida]], and described his upbringing as \"poor\".<ref name=Contorno>{{cite web |url=https://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/12/18/as-trump-mulled-chief-of-staff-pick-u-s-rep-mark-meadowss-usf-degree-was-fixed-on-wikipedia/ |title=U.S. Rep. Mark Meadows's degree fixed on Wikipedia |work=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |author=Steve Contorno |date=December 18, 2018 |accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref> He has said he was a \"fat nerd\" who went on a diet after a classmate rejected him for a date.<ref name=Contorno/> Meadows attended [[Florida State University]] for one year in 1977\u201378.<ref name=Contorno/> Meadows incorrectly claimed to hold a [[Bachelor of Arts]] from the [[University of South Florida]] for many years in his official biography maintained by the Office of the Historian of the U.S. House of Representatives. In actuality he graduated from the [[University of South Florida]] with an [[associate degree|Associate of Arts]].<ref name=Contorno/> \n\nIn 1987 Meadows started \"Aunt D's\", a small restaurant in [[Highlands, North Carolina]]. He later sold it and used the proceeds to start a real estate development company in the [[Tampa, Florida]], area.<ref>{{cite news |last=Parker |first=Brittney |date=October 18, 2012 |title=Candidate Profiles Continue as Election Looms: 11th Congressional District Seat; Mark Meadows |url=http://www.maconnews.com/news/3796-candidate-profiles-continue-as-election-looms |newspaper=Macon County News |location=Franklin, NC |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150623051246/http://www.maconnews.com/news/3796-candidate-profiles-continue-as-election-looms |archivedate=June 23, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nWhile living in Highlands, Meadows served as chairman of the Republican Party in [[Macon County, North Carolina|Macon County]], and was a delegate to several state and national Republican conventions.<ref>{{cite news |date=November 7, 2012 |title=Election 2012: Winner U.S. Representative NC-11; Mark Meadows |url=http://projects.wsj.com/campaign2012/candidates/view/mark-meadows--NC-H |newspaper=Wall Street Journal |location=New York, NY}}</ref>\n\nMeadows previously served on North Carolina's Board for Economic Development in Western North Carolina.<ref>{{cite news |date=February 12, 2012 |title=Meadows Officially Enters Race for Shuler's Seat |url=http://www.blueridgenow.com/article/20120216/articles/120219824 |newspaper=BlueRidgeNow.com |location=Hendersonville, NC}}</ref> In 2011 he moved to [[Glenville, North Carolina]]. In 2016 he sold his house and moved into an apartment in Biltmore Park, a mixed-use community in Asheville, NC, while deciding where to buy next in either Henderson or Buncombe counties.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.citizen-times.com/story/news/local/2017/04/01/mark-meadows-has-taken-chances-rapid-rise-power/99865648/|title=Mark Meadows has taken chances in rapid rise to power|work=Citizen Times|access-date=October 13, 2017|language=en}}</ref> He is the owner of Highlands Properties, which specializes in construction and land development.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bowling |first=Caitlin |date=October 31, 2012 |title=Meadows Touts Rise as Self-Made Businessman |url=http://www.smokymountainnews.com/news/item/9204-meadows-touts-rise-as-self-made-businessman |newspaper=Smoky Mountain News |location=Waynesville, NC}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 Meadows sold 134 acres of land in [[Dinosaur, Colorado]], to a [[Young Earth creationism|young earth creationist]] group. He appeared in the film ''Raising the Allosaur: The True Story of a Rare Dinosaur and the Home Schoolers Who Found It''.<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/mark-meadows-and-the-undisclosed-dinosaur-property |title=Mark Meadows and the Dinosaur Property |last=Bethea |first=Charles |magazine=[[The New Yorker]] |language=en |access-date=2020-01-05 |date=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Tenure===\nMeadows has signed the [[Contract from America]], a set of ten policies assembled by the [[Tea Party movement]].<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web |title= Contract from America |url= http://votesmart.org/public-statement/667797/ |work= Project Vote Smart |accessdate= October 9, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"reform\">{{cite web |title= Mark Meadows on Government Reform |url= http://www.ontheissues.org/NC/Mark_Meadows_Government_Reform.htm |work= On the Issues |accessdate= October 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nMeadows voted against disaster relief spending for October 2012\u2019s [[Hurricane Sandy]], which struck the [[Northeastern United States]] and caused severe damage.<ref name=\"Elis\">{{cite news |last=Elis |first=Niv |date=August 29, 2017 |title=Freedom Caucus chair: Disaster funding doesn't need budget offsets |url=https://thehill.com/policy/finance/budget/348450-freedom-caucus-chair-disaster-funding-doesnt-need-budget-offsets |work=The Hill |location=Washington, DC}}</ref> He was one of several Republicans who claimed the funding bill contained [[pork barrel|pork-barrel]] spending that had nothing to do with hurricane relief, a claim the bill's supporters denied.<ref name=\"Elis\"/><ref name=\"Bouie\">{{cite news |last=Bouie |first=Jamelle |date=August 30, 2017 |title=Help to Those Who Help Themselves |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2017/08/why-the-gop-flip-flops-on-federal-disaster-relief.html |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |location=New York, NY}}</ref> Meadows's opposition to Sandy relief was recalled in 2017 news accounts after he and many Republicans who had opposed it voted in favor of disaster aid following [[Hurricane Harvey]], which caused massive damage in Louisiana and Texas that August.<ref name=\"Elis\"/><ref name=\"Bouie\"/> Critics alleged that Republicans were hypocritically opposing spending in states with Democratic majorities while supporting it in Republican states.<ref name=\"Ledyard\">{{cite news |last1=King |first1=Ledyard |last2=Jackson |first2=Herb |date=August 28, 2017 |title=Officials hope Congress does not repeat disaster aid battle that followed Superstorm Sandy |url=https://www.freep.com/story/news/politics/2017/08/28/officials-hope-congress-does-not-repeat-disaster-aid-battle-followed-superstorm-sandy/608982001/ |work=[[Detroit Free Press]] |location=Detroit, MI}}</ref> Republicans, including Meadows, claimed the situations were different because the Harvey spending bill contained no \"pork\".<ref name=\"Ledyard\"/> A [[Congressional Research Service]] review determined that the Sandy spending bill's funds were almost all devoted to recovery from Sandy.<ref>{{cite news |last=Qiu |first=Linda |date=August 30, 2017 |title=Was 2013 Hurricane Sandy Relief Package 'Full of Pork'? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/30/us/politics/hurricane-sandy-relief-fact-check.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |location=New York, NY}}</ref>\n\nMeadows introduced the [[Hezbollah International Financing Prevention Act of 2014]], a bill that would impose sanctions on foreign financial institutions that facilitate transactions or money laundering on behalf of [[Hezbollah]] or its agents.<ref name=\"cbo4411\">{{cite web |title= CBO - H.R. 4411 |url= http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45523 |publisher= Congressional Budget Office |accessdate= July 23, 2014}}</ref> Hezbollah is designated a terrorist organization in the United States.<ref name=\"cbo4411\"/> The bill passed in the House on July 22, 2014.<ref name=\"ToughenSanctions1\">{{cite news |last1= Marcos |first1= Cristina |title= House votes to toughen sanctions on Hezbollah |url= http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/213053-house-votes-to-toughen-sanctions-on-hezbollah |accessdate= July 23, 2014 |work= The Hill |date= July 22, 2014}}</ref> Meadows said that \"we must pass this legislation to make sure that we can do is cripple their ability to finance and put people out of harm's way.\"<ref name=\"ToughenSanctions1\"/>\n\nOn July 23, 2014, Meadows introduced the [[Federal Records Accountability Act of 2014]], a bill that would change the record-keeping requirements about some types of communications to ensure that information is not lost.<ref name=\"WashTimesMcElhatton\">{{cite news |last1= McElhatton |first1=Jim |title= House federal records plan would prevent repeat of IRS email scandal |url= http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2014/jul/24/house-federal-records-plan-would-prevent-repeat-of|accessdate= September 18, 2014 |work= The Washington Times |date= July 24, 2014}}</ref> The bill would make it easier to fire a person who willfully and unlawfully concealed, removed, mutilated, obliterated, falsified, or destroyed any record, book, or other thing in the custody of such employee.<ref name=\"5170sum\">{{cite web |title= H.R. 5170 - Summary |date= 2016 |url= https://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/5170 |publisher= United States Congress |accessdate= September 18, 2014}}</ref> It would also ban federal employees from using instant messaging for work purposes.<ref name=\"WashTimesMcElhatton\"/>\n\nMeadows served as chair of the [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Government Operations|Subcommittee on Government Operations]] up until June 20, 2015, when fellow Republican congressman [[Jason Chaffetz]] removed him from the position. A member of the House Republican leadership, Chaffetz removed Meadows due to Meadows's vote against a procedural motion the Republican leadership presented.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/mark-meadows-explains-overthrow-boehner|title=Meadows Explains Effort to Overthrow Boehner|last=Dumain|first=Emma|date=2015-07-29|access-date=2020-01-03|last2=Fuller|first2=Matt|language=en|last3=Dumain|first3=Emma|last4=Fuller|first4=Matt}}</ref> Meadows was one of 34 Republicans who voted against the motion, which allowed for consideration of President [[Barack Obama]]'s request for fast-track authority on trade agreements. Speaker [[John Boehner]] supported the measure, but many Republicans felt it gave too much power to Democrats and Obama specifically.<ref name=\"auto7\">{{cite web |last= Sherman |first=Jake |title= Jason Chaffetz strips Meadows of subcommittee chairmanship |url= http://www.politico.com/story/2015/06/chaffetz-strips-meadows-of-subcommittee-chairmanship-119252.html |work= Politico |date= June 20, 2015 |accessdate= June 22, 2015 }}</ref> Chaffetz's action was seen as controversial, with many prominent Republican politicians, including Texas senator [[Ted Cruz]], speaking out against the punishment.\n\nOn July 28, 2015, Meadows filed a [[motion to vacate]] the chair in order to strip Boehner from his leadership position. This action was widely seen as an escalation of the feud between a faction of conservatives and the GOP leadership. Conservatives had long urged a coup against Boehner, whom they viewed as too eager to make deals with Democrats.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news |url= http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2015/jul/28/john-boehner-coup-mark-meadows-files-motion-oust-h/ |title= John Boehner coup: Mark Meadows files motion to oust House Speaker |newspaper= The Washington Times |date= July 28, 2015 |access-date= March 25, 2017 |first1=S.A. |last1=Miller |first2=Tom |last2= Howell Jr. |department= Politics }}</ref>\n\nOn January 29, 2019, Meadows told newly seated representative [[Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez]] that lawmakers need more than three days' notice to attend questioning because they are busy and not just \"sitting around eating bonbons.\" The pair became confrontational during the first meeting of the Oversight and Reform Committee since Democrats took control of the House, the first time he and she appeared at a meeting together. He told Chairman [[Elijah Cummings]] that members should get five days' notice before hearing questioning of witnesses by staff attorneys. Ocasio-Cortez asked Cummings if Republicans, when controlling the committee in the 115th Congress, gave members more notice to make arrangements, to which he replied in the negative.<ref name=\"auto5\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20190201155208/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/congress/mark-meadows-to-alexandria-ocasio-cortez-lawmakers-are-busy-not-just-sitting-around-eating-bonbons Mark Meadows to Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez: Lawmakers are busy, not 'just sitting around eating bonbons'], ''[[Washington Examiner]]'', Katelyn Caralle, January 29, 2019. Retrieved February 6, 2018.</ref>\n\nMeadows is serving as ranking member of the [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|House Oversight Committee]], pending his assumption of office as White House chief of staff.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zanona |first1=Melanie |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/02/11/jim-jordan-mark-meadows-congress-committees-113911 |title=Jim Jordan, Mark Meadows picked as top Republicans on key committees |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |work=Politico |date=February 11, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===2013 federal government shutdown===\nMeadows has been described as playing an important part of the [[United States federal government shutdown of 2013]].<ref name=\"architect\">{{cite news |last=Caldwell |first= Leigh Ann |title= Architect of the brink: Meet the man behind the government shutdown |url= http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/27/politics/house-tea-party/index.html |accessdate= October 8, 2013 |newspaper= CNN |date= October 1, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"constituents\">{{cite news |last=Ostendorff |first=John |title= Meadows says constituents back his shutdown fight |url= http://www.citizen-times.com/article/20131003/NEWS/310030079/Meadows-says-constituents-back-his-shutdown-fight |accessdate= October 8, 2013 |newspaper= Asheville Citizen-Times |date=October 3, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"road\">{{cite news |last=Straw |first= Joseph |title=Tea Party-backed Rep. Mark Meadows put government on road to shutdown |url= http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/meadows-put-government-road-shutdown-article-1.1472233 |newspaper= New York Daily News |date= September 30, 2013 |accessdate= October 8, 2013}}</ref> On August 21, 2013, he wrote an [[open letter]] to Boehner and Majority Leader [[Eric Cantor]] encouraging them to \"affirmatively de-fund the implementation and enforcement of Obamacare in any relevant appropriations bills brought to the House floor in the 113th Congress, including any continuing appropriations bill.\"<ref name=\"auto8\">{{cite web |last=Meadows |first=Mark |title=Letter to Boehner and Cantor |url=http://meadows.house.gov/uploads/Meadows_DefundLetter.pdf |publisher=Meadows.house.gov |accessdate=October 8, 2013 |date=August 21, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131006003805/http://meadows.house.gov/uploads/Meadows_DefundLetter.pdf |archivedate=October 6, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"encouraging\">{{cite news |title= U.S. Rep. Mark Meadows Sends Letter to Boehner, Cantor Encouraging House Leadership to Defund Obamacare |url= http://www.hcpress.com/politics/u-s-rep-mark-meadows-sends-letter-to-boehner-cantor-encouraging-house-leadership-to-defund-obamacare.html |accessdate= October 8, 2013 |newspaper= High County Press |date= August 22, 2013 }}</ref> The document was signed by 79 of Meadows's colleagues in the House.<ref name=architect/><ref name=encouraging/> [[Heritage Action]] (which opened operations in North Carolina in January 2011<ref name=\"heritage\">{{cite news |title= Heritage Foundation sinks its roots in N.C. |author= Rob Christensen |url= http://www.newsobserver.com/2011/01/11/912355/heritage-foundation-sinks-its.html |work=[[The News & Observer]] |date=January 11, 2011 |accessdate= October 11, 2013 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131014125909/http://www.newsobserver.com/2011/01/11/912355/heritage-foundation-sinks-its.html |archivedate= October 14, 2013 }}</ref>), ran critical Internet advertisements in the districts of 100 Republican lawmakers who failed to sign the letter.<ref name=\"Stolberg2013\">{{cite news |last= Stolberg |first=Sheryl Gay |last2= McIntyre |first2=Mike |title=A federal budget crisis months in the planning |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/06/us/a-federal-budget-crisis-months-in-the-planning.html|newspaper=The New York Times |date= October 5, 2013 |accessdate= October 11, 2013}}</ref> The letter has been described as controversial within the Republican Party.<ref name=architect/><ref name=\"missive\">{{cite news |last=Omarzu |first=Tim |title= The letter behind the shutdown; GOP missive urges defunding of Obamacare |url= http://timesfreepress.com/news/2013/oct/04/the-letter-behind-the-shutdown/ |accessdate= October 8, 2013 |newspaper= Times Free Press |date= October 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]'' said Meadows put the federal government on the road to shutdown, saying calls to defund Obamacare through spending bills languished until Meadows wrote his letter.<ref name=road/> Meadows downplayed his influence, saying \"I'm one of 435 members and a very small part of this.\"<ref name=road/> CNN described Meadows as the \"architect of the brink\" for his letter suggesting that Obamacare be defunded in any continuing appropriations bill.<ref name=architect/> Meadows said that sensationalized his role.<ref name=constituents/>\n\nJohn Ostendorff of the ''Asheville Citizen-Times'' wrote that Meadows \"said it's best to close the government in the short term to win a delay on 'Obamacare', despite the potential negative impact on the economy.\"<ref name=constituents/> Ostendorff wrote that Meadows said he was doing what [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]] members in [[Western North Carolina]] wanted him to do.<ref name=constituents/> Meadows said his constituents wanted him to fight against Obamacare \"regardless of consequences.\"<ref name=architect/> Jane Bilello, head of the [[Asheville, North Carolina|Asheville]] Tea Party, said Meadows \"truly represents us\" on the issue of Obamacare.<ref name=architect/> Meadows reportedly holds conference calls with members of the Asheville Tea Party, telling them what's going on in Congress and about challenges he faces promoting their agenda.<ref name=architect/>\n\nIn public comments, Meadows said he was working on a compromise that involved passing appropriations bills that would fund only parts of the government, such as a [[October 2013 mini-continuing resolutions|bill]] to fund the National Park Service, [[Smithsonian Institution]], [[National Gallery of Art]], and [[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum]], and a [[October 2013 mini-continuing resolutions|bill]] to fund the [[National Institutes of Health]]. But partial or \"mini\" funding bills were rejected by the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] majority in the [[United States Senate]].<ref name=constituents/>\n\n===Resolution to remove Speaker Boehner===\nOn July 28, 2015, Meadows filed a resolution<ref name=\"resolution\">{{cite web |url= http://i2.cdn.turner.com/cnn/2015/images/07/28/meadows.hres.385.pdf |title= Resolution Declaring the office of Speaker of the House vacant |first= Mark |last= Meadows |date= July 28, 2015 |accessdate= July 29, 2015 }}</ref> to vote on removing [[John Boehner]] as [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|speaker of the House]].<ref name=\"tries\">{{cite news |title= Mark Meadows Tries to Boot Boehner From Speakership |work= National Journal |date= July 29, 2015 |accessdate= July 29, 2015 |first= Daniel |last= Neewhauser |url= http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress/mark-meadows-tries-to-boot-boehner-from-speakership-20150728 }}</ref> If the resolution passed, the House would then vote to elect a new speaker.<ref name= tries/>\n\nBecause Meadows filed it as a nonprivileged resolution, it was sent to the [[United States House Committee on Rules|House Committee on Rules]] for a vote first, rather than the House floor.<ref name= tries/> The Committee on Rules was considered to have many members who were loyal to Boehner, so the resolution was seen as unlikely to move forward.<ref name= tries/>\n\nMeadows said he filed the resolution because Boehner had \"endeavored to consolidate power, bypassing the majority\" of Congress; \"through inaction, caused the power of Congress to atrophy,\" \"uses the power of the office to punish Members who vote according to their conscience\"; \"has intentionally provided for voice votes on consequential and controversial legislation to be taken without notice and with few Members present\"; \"uses the legislative calendar to create crises for the American People\"; allowed members less than three days to review legislation before voting; and limited meaningful debate on the House floor.<ref name= resolution/> The resolution received support from Congressman [[Walter B. Jones Jr.]]<ref name=\"oustingboehner\">{{cite news|last1=Bresnahan|first1=John|title=John Boehner: Bid to boot him 'no big deal'|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/07/gop-leaders-ignore-attempt-john-boehner-ouster-120771.html|accessdate=July 29, 2015|publisher=Politico|date=July 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nBoehner responded, \"Listen, you have a member here and a member there who are off the reservation. No big deal ... Listen, this is one member. All right. I've got broad support amongst my colleagues. And frankly, it isn't even deserving of a vote.\"<ref name=\"ousting\">{{cite news|last1=Fox|first1=Lauren|title=John Boehner's Not Giving Mark Meadows the Chance to Oust Him|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress/john-boehner-s-not-giving-meadows-the-chance-to-oust-him-20150729|accessdate=July 29, 2015|publisher=National Journal|date=July 29, 2015}}</ref> On September 25, 2015, Boehner announced his intention to resign as speaker.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2015/09/25/john-boehner-resigns-house-speaker/72793398/|title=Amid revolt, Boehner steps aside to avoid 'irreparable harm' to Congress|last=Shesgreen|first=Deirdre|date=September 26, 2015|work=USA Today|access-date=August 23, 2016|via=}}</ref> He officially resigned on October 31, 2015.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.cleveland.com/open/index.ssf/2015/10/john_boehner_exits_john_kasich.html|title=John Boehner exits, John Kasich books Stephen Colbert: Ohio Politics Roundup|last=Gomez|first=Harry|date=October 30, 2015|work=cleveland.com|access-date=August 23, 2016|via=}}</ref>\n\n===Controversies over chief of staff, education, and sexual harassment===\n\nA group of employees reported to Meadows's deputy chief of staff in October 2014 that they were uncomfortable with Meadows's then chief of staff, Kenny West, calling his behavior \"inappropriate towards them\". Meadows asked Representative [[Trey Gowdy]]'s chief of staff to interview the employees, and Meadows eventually limited or prohibited West's presence in Meadows's offices.<ref name=\"controversy\">{{cite news|last1=Troyan|first1=Mary|title=Ethics probe of Rep. Mark Meadows continues|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2016/08/17/ethics-probe-rep-mark-meadows-continues/88903504/|access-date=January 24, 2018|publisher=USA Today|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAlthough West resigned after the employees accused him of inappropriate behavior, he remained on the House payroll in violation of House rules, according to an independent House Ethics Committee investigation. Meadows paid West $58,125 from April 2015 to August 2015 even though he was no longer working in Meadows's office. There is \"substantial reason to believe that Representative Meadows retained an employee who did not perform duties commensurate with the compensation the employee received and certified that the compensation met applicable House standards, in violation of House rules and standards of conduct,\" the [[Office of Congressional Ethics]] report said.\n\nPrior to December 2018, Meadows claimed to have received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree.<ref name=Contorno/>  When questions about his credentials arose during media speculation that he was under consideration to serve as White House chief of staff, Meadows amended his official House biography and other sources to indicate that his degree was an associate, not a bachelor's.<ref name=Contorno/>\n\nIn November 2018 the House Ethics Committee fined Meadows over $40,000 after concluding he \"did not do enough to address\" sexual harassment allegations against West. The committee concluded Meadows took \"immediate and appropriate steps\" by separating West from female staffers and requesting an investigation, but noted that West retained his title and \"apparent authority over staff\" during this period. \"Representative Meadows could have and should have done more to ensure that his congressional office was free from discrimination or the perception of discrimination,\" the committee wrote. The committee fined Meadows $40,625 \"for Mr. West's salary that was not commensurate with his work.\" ''The Daily Beast'' previously reported that a former aide told the committee Meadows and other top staff members in his office were aware of West's behavior before it was publicly reported.<ref name=\"ongoingcontroversy\">{{cite news|last1=Stein|first1=Sam|title=Ex-Mark Meadows Aide Says Sexual Harassment in Congressman's Office Was Known Earlier Than Reported|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/ex-mark-meadows-aide-says-sexual-harassment-in-congressmans-office-was-known-earlier-than-reported|accessdate=January 24, 2018|publisher=The Daily Beast}}</ref>\n\n'''Committee assignments'''\n\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Africa, Global Health, Global Human Rights and International Organizations|Subcommittee on Africa, Global Health, Global Human Rights and International Organizations]]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Middle East and North Africa|Subcommittee on the Middle East and North Africa]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]]'''\n**  [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Government Operations|Subcommittee on Government Operations]] (Chairman)<ref>[https://meadows.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=54 Meadows named chair of Subcommittee on Government Operations], January 24, 2017</ref>\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Economic Growth, Job Creation and Regulatory Affairs|Subcommittee on Economic Growth, Job Creation and Regulatory Affairs]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]]'''\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Aviation|Subcommittee on Aviation]]\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Economic Development, Public Buildings and Emergency Management|Subcommittee on Economic Development, Public Buildings and Emergency Management]]\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment|Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment]]\n\n'''Caucus memberships'''\n\n* [[Congressional Western Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://westerncaucus.house.gov/about/membership.htm|format=|publisher=Congressional Western Caucus|date=|accessdate=July 18, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[U.S.-Japan Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://usjapancaucus-castro.house.gov/members|format=| publisher=U.S. - Japan Caucus|date=|accessdate=December 14, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Freedom Caucus|House Freedom Caucus]]\n*[[Second Amendment Caucus]]\n\n===Elections===\n\n====2012====\n{{See also|2012 United States House of Representatives elections in North Carolina#District 11}}\nIn late 2011 Meadows announced he was running for Congress in North Carolina's 11th congressional district, for the seat being vacated by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] incumbent [[Heath Shuler]]. The district had been significantly altered in [[gerrymandering|redistricting]]. New lines were drawn straight through the middle of Warren Wilson College. Notably, it lost most of [[Asheville, North Carolina|Asheville]] to the [[North Carolina's 10th congressional district|10th district]], while picking up some heavily Republican territory in the foothills. The old 11th had a slight Republican lean, but the new 11th was on paper the most Republican district in the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/11/15/gerrymandering-5k-asheville-north-carolina-215829|title=I Ran the Worst 5K of My Life So I Could Explain Gerrymandering to You|last=Markovich|first=Jeremy|date=15 November 2017|website=Politico|access-date=23 March 2019}}</ref> In 2011 the North Carolina state legislature redrew the congressional districts based on updated population information from the 2010 census.<ref name=\"redistricting\"/> As a result the district is now 91.2% White, 3.0% Black, 1.4% Native American and 1.0% Asian.<ref name=\"redistricting\">{{cite web|url=http://ballotpedia.org/wiki/index.php/North_Carolina's_11th_congressional_district|title=North Carolina's 11th Congressional District - Ballotpedia|author=|date=|website=ballotpedia.org}}</ref> District 11 now includes Buncombe (Asheville), Clay, Cherokee, Graham, Haywood (Waynesville), Henderson (Hendersonville), Jackson (Sylva), Macon (Franklin), McDowell (Marion), Madison, Polk, Swain, Transylvania (Brevard) and Yancey (Burnsville) counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ballotpedia.org/wiki/images/c/c2/NC11.jpg|title=NC11 Map|author=|date=|website=ballotpedia.org}}</ref><ref group=\"Notes\">District 10, with three counties, (Burke (Morganton), Mitchell and Rutherford) that border on District 11, also includes the counties of Avery, Caldwell, Catawba (Hickory and Newton), Cleveland (Shelby), Gaston (Gastonia) and Lincoln (Lincolnton).</ref>\n\nMeadows won the July 2012 Republican primary runoff,<ref>{{cite news|title=Mark Meadows sweeps 11th congressional GOP run-off|url=http://www.maconnews.com/news/state--region/3317-mark-meadows-sweeps-11th-congressional-gop-run-off|accessdate=August 31, 2012|newspaper=The Macon County News|date=July 19, 2012|author=Parker, Brittney|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021014858/http://www.maconnews.com/news/state--region/3317-mark-meadows-sweeps-11th-congressional-gop-run-off|archivedate=October 21, 2013}}</ref> and in the November general election faced Democratic nominee Hayden Rogers, who had been Shuler's chief of staff. On August 28 Meadows spoke at the [[2012 Republican National Convention]] in Tampa.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hendersonvillelightning.com/blog/2012/uncategorized/meadows-back-on-with-tuesday-slot-at-convention/ |title=Meadows back on with Tuesday slot at convention |newspaper=Henderson Lightning |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014123759/http://www.hendersonvillelightning.com/blog/2012/uncategorized/meadows-back-on-with-tuesday-slot-at-convention/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 14, 2013 |date=August 27, 2012 |department=Mossblog |access-date=March 25, 2017 }}</ref> He won the general election with approximately 57% of the vote<ref>{{cite web|url=http://results.enr.clarityelections.com/NC/42923/114047/Web01/en/summary.html|title=NC State Board of Elections|author=|date=|website=clarityelections.com}}</ref> and took office in January 2013.\n\n====2014====\n{{See also|2014 United States House of Representatives elections in North Carolina#District 11}}\nMeadows was reelected with 62.9% of the vote.\n\n====2016====\n{{See also|2016 United States House of Representatives elections in North Carolina#District 11}}\nMeadows appeared with candidate [[Donald Trump]] on the campaign trail in Winston-Salem, North Carolina in July 2016 just after the Republican National Convention, leading the crowd in a chant, \"Lock her up\", an anti-Hillary Clinton refrain.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jenna |last=Johnson |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/07/26/at-donald-trumps-north-carolina-rally-the-warm-up-acts-nearly-upstaged-the-nominee/ |department=Post Politics |title=At Donald Trump's North Carolina rally, the warm-up acts nearly upstaged the nominee |date=July 26, 2016 |newspaper=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nMeadows won re-election with 64.1% of the vote.\n\n====2018====\n[[File:Mark Meadows (39818366944).jpg|right|thumb|Mark Meadows at 2018 [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] (CPAC) in [[National Harbor, Maryland]]]]\n{{See also|2018 United States House of Representatives elections in North Carolina#District 11}}\nMeadows won reelection to his seat in the November 6, 2018 election, receiving 59% of the vote to his Democratic opponent Phillip Price's 38%.<ref>{{Cite web|title=North Carolina's 11th Congressional District election, 2018|url=https://ballotpedia.org/North_Carolina%27s_11th_Congressional_District_election,_2018|website=ballotpedia.org}}</ref>\n\nDuring the campaign Meadows supported President Trump\u2019s agenda, calling him a \"conservative president\" in 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/mark-meadows-donald-trump-is-a-conservative|title=Mark Meadows: 'Donald Trump is a conservative'|date=2017-03-31|website=Washington Examiner|language=en|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref> and suggesting that Republicans who didn't support Trump should be removed from office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/355311-meadows-time-to-eject-lawmakers-who-dont-back-trump|title=Meadows: Time to 'eject' lawmakers who don't back Trump|last=Rowland|first=Geoffrey|date=2017-10-13|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref> Trump\u2019s son-in-law [[Jared Kushner]] attended a private fundraiser for Meadows.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/09/01/kushner-fundraises-for-mark-meadows-242244|title=Kushner fundraises for Mark Meadows|website=[[Politico]]|date=2017-09-01}}</ref> In January 2018 Meadows traveled to [[Davos]], Switzerland, with a congressional delegation for the World Economic Forum, along with a White House delegation including Trump and cabinet members including Treasury Secretary [[Steven Mnuchin]], Secretary of State [[Rex Tillerson]], and Energy Secretary [[Rick Perry]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/government-shutdown-deal-saves-congressional-trip-to-davos-2018-1|title=The deal to end the government shutdown saved the congressional trip to an elite gathering in Davos, Switzerland|last=Perticone|first=Joe|date=January 22, 2018|accessdate=January 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180124083332/http://www.businessinsider.com/government-shutdown-deal-saves-congressional-trip-to-davos-2018-1|archivedate=January 24, 2018 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.citizen-times.com/story/news/politics/elections/2018/01/26/meadows-attends-economic-forum-davos-switzerland-speaks-panel/1070763001/|title=Mark Meadows attends economic forum in Switzerland, speaks on panel|last=Barrett|first=Mark|date=January 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2020====\n\nOn December 19, 2019, Meadows announced that he would not seek reelection [[2020 United States House of Representatives elections in North Carolina#District 11|in 2020]].<ref name=\"won't run\">{{cite news |last=McPherson |first=Lindsey |date=December 29, 2019 |title=North Carolina's Mark Meadows won't run for reelection |url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/congress/north-carolinas-mark-meadows-wont-run-reelection |work=[[Roll Call]] |location=[[Washington, D.C.]] |access-date=December 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==White House chief of staff==\nIn December 2018, Meadows was vocal about his desire to work in the White House as [[White House Chief of Staff|chief of staff]] upon the January 2019 departure of [[John F. Kelly]].<ref>Caralle, Katelyn. (December 10, 2018). \"Mark Meadows wants to be Trump's chief of staff.\" [https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/white-house/mark-meadows-wants-to-be-trumps-chief-of-staff Washington Examiner website] Retrieved December 10, 2018.</ref>\n\nOn March 6, 2020, Trump named Meadows the next White House chief of staff,<ref>{{cite tweet |number=1236096307103707136 |title=I am pleased to announce that Congressman Mark Meadows will become White House Chief of Staff |date=March 6, 2020 |access-date=March 6, 2020 |first=Donald J. |last=Trump |author-link=Donald Trump |user=realDonaldTrump |language=en}}</ref> succeeding acting chief of staff [[Mick Mulvaney]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Baker |first=Peter |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/06/us/politics/trump-mark-meadows-mick-mulvaney.html |title=Trump Names Mark Meadows Chief of Staff, Ousting Mick Mulvaney |date=March 6, 2020 |work=The New York Times |access-date=March 6, 2020 |url-status=live |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=Zeke |last2=Colvin |first2=Jill |last3=Taylor |first3=Andrew |title=Meadows toggles between legislator, White House roles |url=https://apnews.com/b99ed04440019680c785a897df91548a |date=March 27, 2020 |work=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> Meadows resigned from the House on March 30, 2020,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lesniewski |first1=Niels |last2=McPherson |first2=Lindsey |title=Rep. Mark Meadows resigns to become White House chief of staff |url=https://www.rollcall.com/2020/03/30/rep-mark-meadows-resigns-to-become-white-house-chief-of-staff/ |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=[[Roll Call]] |date=March 30, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> and began his new role the next day. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/rep-mark-meadows-resigns-congress-take-chief-staff-role-n1172621|title=Rep. Mark Meadows resigns from Congress to become Trump's chief of staff|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n== Political positions ==\n\n=== Abortion ===\nMeadows is [[pro-life]] and has called [[Abortion in the United States|abortion]] a tragedy. He opposes federal funding for abortion and believes parents should be notified of underage abortion procedures. He also opposes churches and other religious sites being forced to provide [[birth control]] options.<ref name=\"issues\"/>\n\n=== Birtherism ===\nWhile running for office in June 2012, Meadows said, \"2012 is the time we are going to send Mr. Obama home to Kenya or wherever it is,\" implying that President Obama was [[Barack Obama citizenship conspiracy theories|not born in the United States]]. He made a similar comment later that month. When asked about his comment, Meadows said it was \"a non-issue\", \"probably a poor choice of words on my part\" and that he ultimately believed that Obama was an American citizen.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/north-carolina-candidate-appears-to-flirt-with-birtherism|title=North Carolina: Candidate Appears to Flirt With Birtherism|last=Miller|first=Joshua|date=2012-06-26|access-date=2019-02-28|last2=Miller|first2=Joshua|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Budget ===\nMeadows is part of a group that has advocated for a [[balanced budget amendment]] to the United States Constitution. He opposed the recent federal stimulus spending and has expressed a desire for the federal spending growth rate to be capped at the inflation rate. He supports a moratorium on all earmarks until the budget has been balanced. Meadows opposes any cuts to military spending levels.<ref name=\"issues\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/NC/Mark_Meadows.htm|title=Mark Meadows : (Republican, district 11)|work=On the Issues}}</ref>\n\n=== Civil rights ===\nIn February 2013 Meadows voted against renewing the [[Violence Against Women Act]]. Meadows has said he casts his votes based not on his personal feelings but on what the majority of his constituents in \"God's Country\" tell him to do.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/nation/2013/06/22/new-district-maps-reaped-rewards-for-gop-congress-but-cost-fewer-moderates-more-gridlock/B6jCugm94tpBvVu77ay0wJ/story.html|title=Turning the political map into a partisan weapon|last=Jan|first=Tracy|date=June 23, 2013|work=The Boston Globe|access-date=January 24, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n=== Environment and energy ===\nIn December 2016 Meadows gave Trump a wish list of regulations to be repealed. It included a demand to get rid of federal funding to study climate change. He also requested Trump repeal several environmental regulations, including the [[Renewable Fuel Standard (United States)|Renewable Fuel Standard]], end the prohibition of drilling oil on federal lands, and pull the US out of the [[Paris Agreement|Paris Climate Agreement]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/12/15/house-conservatives-want-trump-to-undo-regulations-on-fda-climate-uber/|title=House conservatives want Trump to undo regulations on climate, FDA, Uber|website=The Washington Post|access-date=May 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nMeadows has said that [[cap-and-trade]] emission policies are ineffective and have minimal impact on the global environment. He has proposed that the United States tap into oil and gas reserves to keep energy prices low and develop [[United States energy independence|energy independence]]. He supports tapping into off-shore oil and gas supplies.<ref name=\"issues\"/>\n\n=== LGBT rights ===\nMeadows opposes [[same-sex marriage]]. In March 2013, he said that if the Supreme Court allowed gay marriage, it would cause a constitutional crisis if the federal government decided to dismiss state decisions and thus infringe on state's rights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontopmag.com/article.aspx?id=14815&MediaType=1&Category=26|title=Rep. Mark Meadows Warns Of 'Constitutional Crisis' If SCOTUS Rules For Gay Marriage|date=Mar 29, 2013|work=On Top}}</ref>\n\n=== Gun control ===\nMeadows opposes any [[Gun control in the United States|restrictions on gun purchases]] and opposes a national gun registry that would list detailed information about firearm ownership.<ref name=\"issues\"/>\n\n=== Healthcare ===\nMeadows opposes the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] (Obamacare), and has stated that it should be replaced by private enterprise.<ref name=\"issues\"/>\n\nLess than a year after taking office, Meadows wrote the letter that initially urged House Speaker [[John Boehner]] to shut down the government unless the ACA was defunded. Some constituents have criticized him as responsible for the 2013 government shutdown; ''[[The Washington Post]]'' called him its \"chief architect\". His district lost up to $1 million per day during the shutdown because the national parks were closed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/rep-mark-meadows-pushed-for-a-shutdown-what-did-it-bring-his-NC-district-frustration/2013/10/19/d8a1dcf2-380c-11e3-8a0e-4e2cf80831fc_story.html|title=Rep. Mark Meadows pushed for a shutdown. What did it bring his N.C. district? Frustration.|website=The Washington Post|access-date=May 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Meadows voted for a budget resolution that initiated the process of repealing Obamacare.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.healthreformvotes.org/congress/roll-call-votes/h58-115.2017|title=HR 3: A budget resolution to begin the process of repealing the ACA.|work=HealthReformVotes.org|access-date=May 25, 2017|language=en}}</ref> On May 4, 2017, Meadows voted for the [[American Health Care Act of 2017|American Health Care Act]] (AHCA), which would partially repeal and replace Obamacare.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/05/04/us/politics/house-vote-republican-health-care-bill.html|title=How Every Member Voted on the House Health Care Bill|last=Shorey|first=Gregor Aisch, Sarah Almukhtar, Wilson Andrews, Jeremy Bowers, Nate Cohn, K. k Rebecca Lai, Jasmine C. Lee, Alicia Parlapiano, Adam Pearce, Nadja Popovich, Kevin Quealy, Rachel|date=May 4, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 25, 2017|last2=Singhvi|first2=Anjali|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Congressional Budget Office]] (CBO) released numbers about the AHCA's effects on Americans on May 24, 2017, there were several reports that Meadows became emotional after reading about the AHCA's likely effects on those with preexisting conditions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aol.com/article/news/2017/05/25/gop-rep-mark-meadows-reportedly-teared-up-after-reading-analysis-obamacare-replacement-bill-pre-existing-conditions/22109412/|title=GOP Rep. Mark Meadows reportedly teared up after reading Obamacare replacement bill analysis|last=Staff|first=AOL|work=AOL.com|access-date=May 25, 2017|language=en}}</ref> Others reported he cried only after bringing up his family members who had dealt with preexisting conditions, including his sister who had died of breast cancer, and his father who had died of lung cancer. Meadows said he wouldn't \"make a political decision today that affects somebody's sister or father because I wouldn't do it to myself.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/news/politics-government/article152692439.html|title=No, an NC congressman didn't cry about the health bill score|work=charlotteobserver|access-date=May 25, 2017|language=en}}</ref> When asked about the CBO numbers, Meadows said the government should ensure people with preexisting conditions can afford health care, saying, \"The president is committed to making sure preexisting conditions are covered in principle and in practice, which means that funding has to be there to make it work.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/meadows-floats-more-funding-for-repeal-bill-after-cbo-score/article/2624096|title=Meadows floats more funding for repeal bill after CBO score|last=King|first=Robert|work=Washington Examiner|access-date=May 25, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Net neutrality ===\nMeadows opposes regulations that require all internet providers provide [[Net neutrality in the United States|internet at equal speeds to all parties]]. In 2016 he gave Trump a list of regulations to repeal that included net neutrality regulations by the [[Federal Communications Commission]].<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n=== Russia investigation ===\nMeadows, a member of the [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Reform|House Oversight and Government Reform Committee]], has been a harsh critic of Special Counsel Robert Mueller's [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u2013present)|investigation into Russian interference in the 2016 election]]. During Trump's presidency, Meadows regularly conferred with Trump about Mueller's probe.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/16/trump-mueller-russia-probe-doj-documents-592148|title=GOP lawmakers to Trump: Make DOJ release Mueller documents|work=POLITICO|access-date=May 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/bigger-than-watergate-trump-joins-push-by-allies-to-expose-an-fbi-source/2018/05/17/db211542-59ea-11e8-8836-a4a123c359ab_story.html|title='Bigger than Watergate': Trump joins push by allies to expose role of an FBI source|last=Rucker|first=Philip|date=May 17, 2018|work=The Washington Post|access-date=May 18, 2018|last2=Costa|first2=Robert|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|last3=Leonnig|first3=Carol D.|last4=Dawsey|first4=Josh}}</ref> Meadows has been described as a \"Trump ally\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/406008-trump-blasts-fbi-doj-over-strzok-page-media-leak-strategy|title=Trump blasts FBI, DOJ over Strzok-Page 'Media Leak Strategy'|last=Birnbaum|first=Emily|date=September 11, 2018|work=TheHill|access-date=September 11, 2018|language=en}}</ref> In May 2018, Meadows called for a financial audit of the Mueller investigation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/387163-freedom-caucus-chairman-wants-financial-audit-of-mueller-investigation|title=Freedom Caucus chairman wants financial audit of Mueller investigation|last=Delk|first=Josh|date=May 10, 2018|work=TheHill|access-date=May 18, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, along with [[Jim Jordan (American politician)|Jim Jordan]], Meadows called on the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] to \"review allegations that Deputy Attorney General [[Rod Rosenstein]] threatened to subpoena phone records and documents from a House Intelligence Committee staffer\". An aide termed the deputy AG's threats \"downright chilling\". In their written request, they wrote that in his use of investigative powers, Rosenstein retaliated \"against rank-and-file staff members\", therefore abusing his authority.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Brufke |first1=Julie Grace |title=Freedom Caucus lawmakers call on DOJ to probe Rosenstein allegations |url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/397340-freedom-caucus-lawmakers-call-on-doj-to-probe-rosenstein-allegations |website=The Hill |accessdate=July 17, 2018}}</ref> Furthermore, during a ''[[Fox News]]'' interview by [[Laura Ingraham]] that same month, he \"threatened to force a vote on the GOP resolution\" that would impeach the deputy AG. Arguing he could force the resolution to the floor as a \"[[Raise a question of privilege|privileged motion]]\", he elaborated: \"we hope it doesn't have to come to that\". He filed articles of impeachment against Rosenstein on July 25, although the measure cannot be \"brought straight to the House floor\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Birnbaum |first1=Emily |title=Meadows threatens to force a vote on Rosenstein impeachment |url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/398931-republican-threatens-to-force-a-vote-on-rosenstein-impeachment |website=The Hill |accessdate=July 27, 2018}}</ref> Meadows's Democratic opponent in the 2018 election, Phillip Price, condemned the impeachment resolution as an attempt to shut down the Justice Department's investigation of Russian meddling into the 2016 election through \"obstruction of justice.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Democrat rips Meadows' Rosenstein threat as 'obstruction of justice' |url=https://www.hendersonvillelightning.com/four-seasons-politics/7145-democrat-rips-meadows-justice-threat-as-obstruction-of-justice.html |newspaper=Hendersonville Lightning |location=[[Hendersonville, North Carolina]] |accessdate=August 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Taxes ===\nMeadows has signed the [[Taxpayer Protection Pledge]], and he opposes a raise in all taxes, including the income tax. Meadows supports a [[flat tax|flat-rate income tax]] for all earners and a repeal of the raise in the [[capital gains tax]]. He also supports the elimination of the [[Estate tax in the United States|estate tax]].<ref name=\"issues\"/>\n\n=== Trump\u2013Ukraine scandal ===\n{{Further|Trump\u2013Ukraine scandal}}\nOn December 8, 2019, Meadows claimed that Trump never asked a foreign leader to investigate a political rival,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/mark-meadows-trump-ukraine-biden-c43d2e8d-785b-462f-9aa1-b03bc1fa24a5.html|title=\"He didn't do that\": Mark Meadows denies Trump asked Ukraine to investigate political rival|last=Bassou|first=Zachary|date=December 8, 2019|website=Axios|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=December 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/12/08/mark-meadows-trump-ukraine-investigate-rivals-078189|title=Mark Meadows claims Trump did not ask Ukraine to investigate rivals|last=Kullgren|first=Ian|date=2019-12-08|website=POLITICO|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref> despite a transcript of the July 25, 2019 phone call between Trump and Ukrainian President [[Volodymyr Zelensky]] that some interpreted to mean that Trump had asked Zelensky to investigate former Vice President [[Joe Biden]]<ref name=\":2\" /> and in spite of Trump's October 3, 2019 public calling upon [[China]] to investigate Hunter Biden's business activities there while his father was vice president.<ref name=\"Wagner\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-impeachment-whistleblower/2019/10/02/80df829a-e494-11e9-b403-f738899982d2_story.html|title=Live updates: Trump calls for China to investigate Bidens; former Ukraine envoy testifies on Capitol Hill|last1=Wagner|first1=John|date=October 3, 2019|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=December 8, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/us6JC|archive-date=October 2, 2019|last2=Sonmez|first2=Felicia|url-access=limited}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/oct/03/trump-biden-china-investigation-demand|title=Trump calls on China to investigate Biden in extraordinary demand|last=Borger|first=Julian|date=October 3, 2019|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=October 5, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004142600/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/oct/03/trump-biden-china-investigation-demand|archive-date=December 8, 2019|last2=Gambino|first2=Lauren|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Meadows said he would be \"OK\" with a Democratic president doing what Trump did: \u201cWe have Democrat Senators who have done just that.\u201d<ref>{{Citation|title=Meadows: I'd be OK with a Dem doing what Trump did - CNN Video|url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2019/12/08/sotu-meadows-dem.cnn|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref>\n\n=== Wages ===\nMeadows presented a letter to Trump in 2016 that demanded the repeal of the federal requirement that [[public works]] projects pay laborers and mechanics the locally prevailing wages, which was initially made to protect traveling black workers in the South from being paid far less than local workers. The letter also demanded the repeal of the overtime rule from the Obama administration, which said people making less than $47,000 a year must be paid extra for overtime hours, compared to the previous requirement that those making over $23,000 a year could be denied overtime pay if the worker's duties could be considered \"managerial.\" The letter also demanded the end of regulations requiring federal contractors to be paid for sick leave.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=\"Notes\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/North_Carolina/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Mark_Meadows_%5BR-11%5D|Mark Meadows}}\n* {{C-SPAN|Mark Meadows}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=M001187 | votesmart=136459 | fec=H2NC11080 | congress=mark-meadows/2142}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=7684212|name=Mark Meadows}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DRjRNwgdyPE Mark Meadow's Commencement address at Patrick Henry College]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Heath Shuler]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from North Carolina|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[North Carolina's 11th congressional district]]|years=2013\u20132020}}\n{{s-vac}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jim Jordan (American politician)|Jim Jordan]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Ranking Member of the [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Reform|House Oversight Committee]]|years=2020}}\n{{s-aft|after=TBD}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jim Jordan (American politician)|Jim Jordan]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[Freedom Caucus]]|years=2017\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Andy Biggs]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Mick Mulvaney]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[White House Chief of Staff]]|years=2020\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{WHCOS}}\n{{Trump cabinet}}\n{{Current U.S. Cabinet}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 113th\u2013115th [[United States Congress]]es |state=[[United States congressional delegations from North Carolina|North Carolina]]}}\n{{USCongRep/NC/113}}\n{{USCongRep/NC/114}}\n{{USCongRep/NC/115}}\n{{USCongRep-end}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meadows, Mark}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Activists from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:American conservative people]]\n[[Category:American conspiracy theorists]]\n[[Category:Christians from Florida]]\n[[Category:Christians from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Military brats]]\n[[Category:North Carolina Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from Brandon, Florida]]\n[[Category:People from Jackson County, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Tea Party movement activists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date = December 2019}}\n{{short description|U.S. Representative from North Carolina}}\n{{For|other people with the same name|Mark Meadows (disambiguation){{!}}Mark Meadows}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Mark Meadows\n|image        = Mark Meadows, Official Portrait, 113th Congress.jpg\n|office       = 29th [[White House Chief of Staff]]\n|president    = [[Donald Trump]]\n|term_start   = March 31, 2020\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Mick Mulvaney]] (acting)\n|successor    = \n|office1      = Ranking Member of the <br>[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Reform|House Oversight Committee]]\n|term_start1  = March 12, 2020\n|term_end1    = March 30, 2020\n|predecessor1 = [[Jim Jordan (American politician)|Jim Jordan]]\n|successor1   = ''Vacant''\n|office2      = Chair of the House [[Freedom Caucus]]\n|term_start2  = January 3, 2017\n|term_end2    = October 1, 2019\n|predecessor2 = [[Jim Jordan (American politician)|Jim Jordan]]\n|successor2   = [[Andy Biggs]]\n|state3       = [[North Carolina]]\n|district3    = {{ushr|NC|11|11th}}\n|term_start3  = January 3, 2013\n|term_end3    = March 30, 2020\n|predecessor3 = [[Heath Shuler]]\n|successor3   = ''Vacant''\n|birth_name   = Mark Randall Meadows\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1959|7|28}}\n|birth_place  = [[Verdun]], [[France]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|Debbie Meadows|1979}}\n|children     = 2\n|father       = John Robie Meadows\n|education    = [[Florida State University]]<br>([[No Degree|No Degree]])<br>[[University of South Florida]] ([[Associate degree|AA]])\n|website      =    \n}}\n{{Conservatism in the United States}}\n'''Mark Randall Meadows''' (born July 28, 1959) is an American politician who is the 29th and current White House chief of staff. Meadows served as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. representative]] for [[North Carolina's 11th congressional district]] from 2013 to 2020. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] and chaired the [[Freedom Caucus]] from 2017 to 2019. He was considered one of Trump's closest allies in [[United States Congress|Congress]] before his appointment as chief of staff.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/12/10/mark-meadows-trump-white-house-chief-of-staff-1054790|title=Meadows would give Trump a skilled brawler in the White House|publisher=[[Politico]]|date=December 10, 2018|first1=Rachael|last1=Bade|first2=Kyle|last2=Cheney|first3=Eliana|last3=Johnson}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and business career==\nMeadows was born at a [[United States Army]] hospital in [[Verdun]], France, where his father was serving in the Army and his mother worked as a civilian nurse. His mother was from [[Sevierville, Tennessee]], and his father from [[Pineville, Arkansas]].\n\nHe grew up in [[Brandon, Florida]], and described his upbringing as \"poor\".<ref name=Contorno>{{cite web |url=https://www.tampabay.com/florida-politics/buzz/2018/12/18/as-trump-mulled-chief-of-staff-pick-u-s-rep-mark-meadowss-usf-degree-was-fixed-on-wikipedia/ |title=U.S. Rep. Mark Meadows's degree fixed on Wikipedia |work=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |author=Steve Contorno |date=December 18, 2018 |accessdate=December 18, 2018}}</ref> He has said he was a \"fat nerd\" who went on a diet after a classmate rejected him for a date.<ref name=Contorno/> Meadows attended [[Florida State University]] for one year in 1977\u201378.<ref name=Contorno/> Meadows incorrectly claimed to hold a [[Bachelor of Arts]] from the [[University of South Florida]] for many years in his official biography maintained by the Office of the Historian of the U.S. House of Representatives. In actuality he graduated from the [[University of South Florida]] with an [[associate degree|Associate of Arts]].<ref name=Contorno/> \n\nIn 1987 Meadows started \"Aunt D's\", a small restaurant in [[Highlands, North Carolina]]. He later sold it and used the proceeds to start a real estate development company in the [[Tampa, Florida]], area.<ref>{{cite news |last=Parker |first=Brittney |date=October 18, 2012 |title=Candidate Profiles Continue as Election Looms: 11th Congressional District Seat; Mark Meadows |url=http://www.maconnews.com/news/3796-candidate-profiles-continue-as-election-looms |newspaper=Macon County News |location=Franklin, NC |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150623051246/http://www.maconnews.com/news/3796-candidate-profiles-continue-as-election-looms |archivedate=June 23, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nWhile living in Highlands, Meadows served as chairman of the Republican Party in [[Macon County, North Carolina|Macon County]], and was a delegate to several state and national Republican conventions.<ref>{{cite news |date=November 7, 2012 |title=Election 2012: Winner U.S. Representative NC-11; Mark Meadows |url=http://projects.wsj.com/campaign2012/candidates/view/mark-meadows--NC-H |newspaper=Wall Street Journal |location=New York, NY}}</ref>\n\nMeadows previously served on North Carolina's Board for Economic Development in Western North Carolina.<ref>{{cite news |date=February 12, 2012 |title=Meadows Officially Enters Race for Shuler's Seat |url=http://www.blueridgenow.com/article/20120216/articles/120219824 |newspaper=BlueRidgeNow.com |location=Hendersonville, NC}}</ref> In 2011 he moved to [[Glenville, North Carolina]]. In 2016 he sold his house and moved into an apartment in Biltmore Park, a mixed-use community in Asheville, NC, while deciding where to buy next in either Henderson or Buncombe counties.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.citizen-times.com/story/news/local/2017/04/01/mark-meadows-has-taken-chances-rapid-rise-power/99865648/|title=Mark Meadows has taken chances in rapid rise to power|work=Citizen Times|access-date=October 13, 2017|language=en}}</ref> He is the owner of Highlands Properties, which specializes in construction and land development.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bowling |first=Caitlin |date=October 31, 2012 |title=Meadows Touts Rise as Self-Made Businessman |url=http://www.smokymountainnews.com/news/item/9204-meadows-touts-rise-as-self-made-businessman |newspaper=Smoky Mountain News |location=Waynesville, NC}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014 Meadows sold 134 acres of land in [[Dinosaur, Colorado]], to a [[Young Earth creationism|young earth creationist]] group. He appeared in the film ''Raising the Allosaur: The True Story of a Rare Dinosaur and the Home Schoolers Who Found It''.<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/mark-meadows-and-the-undisclosed-dinosaur-property |title=Mark Meadows and the Dinosaur Property |last=Bethea |first=Charles |magazine=[[The New Yorker]] |language=en |access-date=2020-01-05 |date=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Tenure===\nMeadows has signed the [[Contract from America]], a set of ten policies assembled by the [[Tea Party movement]].<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web |title= Contract from America |url= http://votesmart.org/public-statement/667797/ |work= Project Vote Smart |accessdate= October 9, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"reform\">{{cite web |title= Mark Meadows on Government Reform |url= http://www.ontheissues.org/NC/Mark_Meadows_Government_Reform.htm |work= On the Issues |accessdate= October 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\nMeadows voted against disaster relief spending for October 2012\u2019s [[Hurricane Sandy]], which struck the [[Northeastern United States]] and caused severe damage.<ref name=\"Elis\">{{cite news |last=Elis |first=Niv |date=August 29, 2017 |title=Freedom Caucus chair: Disaster funding doesn't need budget offsets |url=https://thehill.com/policy/finance/budget/348450-freedom-caucus-chair-disaster-funding-doesnt-need-budget-offsets |work=The Hill |location=Washington, DC}}</ref> He was one of several Republicans who claimed the funding bill contained [[pork barrel|pork-barrel]] spending that had nothing to do with hurricane relief, a claim the bill's supporters denied.<ref name=\"Elis\"/><ref name=\"Bouie\">{{cite news |last=Bouie |first=Jamelle |date=August 30, 2017 |title=Help to Those Who Help Themselves |url=https://slate.com/news-and-politics/2017/08/why-the-gop-flip-flops-on-federal-disaster-relief.html |work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] |location=New York, NY}}</ref> Meadows's opposition to Sandy relief was recalled in 2017 news accounts after he and many Republicans who had opposed it voted in favor of disaster aid following [[Hurricane Harvey]], which caused massive damage in Louisiana and Texas that August.<ref name=\"Elis\"/><ref name=\"Bouie\"/> Critics alleged that Republicans were hypocritically opposing spending in states with Democratic majorities while supporting it in Republican states.<ref name=\"Ledyard\">{{cite news |last1=King |first1=Ledyard |last2=Jackson |first2=Herb |date=August 28, 2017 |title=Officials hope Congress does not repeat disaster aid battle that followed Superstorm Sandy |url=https://www.freep.com/story/news/politics/2017/08/28/officials-hope-congress-does-not-repeat-disaster-aid-battle-followed-superstorm-sandy/608982001/ |work=[[Detroit Free Press]] |location=Detroit, MI}}</ref> Republicans, including Meadows, claimed the situations were different because the Harvey spending bill contained no \"pork\".<ref name=\"Ledyard\"/> A [[Congressional Research Service]] review determined that the Sandy spending bill's funds were almost all devoted to recovery from Sandy.<ref>{{cite news |last=Qiu |first=Linda |date=August 30, 2017 |title=Was 2013 Hurricane Sandy Relief Package 'Full of Pork'? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/30/us/politics/hurricane-sandy-relief-fact-check.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |location=New York, NY}}</ref>\n\nMeadows introduced the [[Hezbollah International Financing Prevention Act of 2014]], a bill that would impose sanctions on foreign financial institutions that facilitate transactions or money laundering on behalf of [[Hezbollah]] or its agents.<ref name=\"cbo4411\">{{cite web |title= CBO - H.R. 4411 |url= http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45523 |publisher= Congressional Budget Office |accessdate= July 23, 2014}}</ref> Hezbollah is designated a terrorist organization in the United States.<ref name=\"cbo4411\"/> The bill passed in the House on July 22, 2014.<ref name=\"ToughenSanctions1\">{{cite news |last1= Marcos |first1= Cristina |title= House votes to toughen sanctions on Hezbollah |url= http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/house/213053-house-votes-to-toughen-sanctions-on-hezbollah |accessdate= July 23, 2014 |work= The Hill |date= July 22, 2014}}</ref> Meadows said that \"we must pass this legislation to make sure that we can do is cripple their ability to finance and put people out of harm's way.\"<ref name=\"ToughenSanctions1\"/>\n\nOn July 23, 2014, Meadows introduced the [[Federal Records Accountability Act of 2014]], a bill that would change the record-keeping requirements about some types of communications to ensure that information is not lost.<ref name=\"WashTimesMcElhatton\">{{cite news |last1= McElhatton |first1=Jim |title= House federal records plan would prevent repeat of IRS email scandal |url= http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2014/jul/24/house-federal-records-plan-would-prevent-repeat-of|accessdate= September 18, 2014 |work= The Washington Times |date= July 24, 2014}}</ref> The bill would make it easier to fire a person who willfully and unlawfully concealed, removed, mutilated, obliterated, falsified, or destroyed any record, book, or other thing in the custody of such employee.<ref name=\"5170sum\">{{cite web |title= H.R. 5170 - Summary |date= 2016 |url= https://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/5170 |publisher= United States Congress |accessdate= September 18, 2014}}</ref> It would also ban federal employees from using instant messaging for work purposes.<ref name=\"WashTimesMcElhatton\"/>\n\nMeadows served as chair of the [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Government Operations|Subcommittee on Government Operations]] up until June 20, 2015, when fellow Republican congressman [[Jason Chaffetz]] removed him from the position. A member of the House Republican leadership, Chaffetz removed Meadows due to Meadows's vote against a procedural motion the Republican leadership presented.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/mark-meadows-explains-overthrow-boehner|title=Meadows Explains Effort to Overthrow Boehner|last=Dumain|first=Emma|date=2015-07-29|access-date=2020-01-03|last2=Fuller|first2=Matt|language=en|last3=Dumain|first3=Emma|last4=Fuller|first4=Matt}}</ref> Meadows was one of 34 Republicans who voted against the motion, which allowed for consideration of President [[Barack Obama]]'s request for fast-track authority on trade agreements. Speaker [[John Boehner]] supported the measure, but many Republicans felt it gave too much power to Democrats and Obama specifically.<ref name=\"auto7\">{{cite web |last= Sherman |first=Jake |title= Jason Chaffetz strips Meadows of subcommittee chairmanship |url= http://www.politico.com/story/2015/06/chaffetz-strips-meadows-of-subcommittee-chairmanship-119252.html |work= Politico |date= June 20, 2015 |accessdate= June 22, 2015 }}</ref> Chaffetz's action was seen as controversial, with many prominent Republican politicians, including Texas senator [[Ted Cruz]], speaking out against the punishment.\n\nOn July 28, 2015, Meadows filed a [[motion to vacate]] the chair in order to strip Boehner from his leadership position. This action was widely seen as an escalation of the feud between a faction of conservatives and the GOP leadership. Conservatives had long urged a coup against Boehner, whom they viewed as too eager to make deals with Democrats.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news |url= http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2015/jul/28/john-boehner-coup-mark-meadows-files-motion-oust-h/ |title= John Boehner coup: Mark Meadows files motion to oust House Speaker |newspaper= The Washington Times |date= July 28, 2015 |access-date= March 25, 2017 |first1=S.A. |last1=Miller |first2=Tom |last2= Howell Jr. |department= Politics }}</ref>\n\nOn January 29, 2019, Meadows told newly seated representative [[Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez]] that lawmakers need more than three days' notice to attend questioning because they are busy and not just \"sitting around eating bonbons.\" The pair became confrontational during the first meeting of the Oversight and Reform Committee since Democrats took control of the House, the first time he and she appeared at a meeting together. He told Chairman [[Elijah Cummings]] that members should get five days' notice before hearing questioning of witnesses by staff attorneys. Ocasio-Cortez asked Cummings if Republicans, when controlling the committee in the 115th Congress, gave members more notice to make arrangements, to which he replied in the negative.<ref name=\"auto5\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20190201155208/https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/congress/mark-meadows-to-alexandria-ocasio-cortez-lawmakers-are-busy-not-just-sitting-around-eating-bonbons Mark Meadows to Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez: Lawmakers are busy, not 'just sitting around eating bonbons'], ''[[Washington Examiner]]'', Katelyn Caralle, January 29, 2019. Retrieved February 6, 2018.</ref>\n\nMeadows is serving as ranking member of the [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|House Oversight Committee]], pending his assumption of office as White House chief of staff.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zanona |first1=Melanie |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/02/11/jim-jordan-mark-meadows-congress-committees-113911 |title=Jim Jordan, Mark Meadows picked as top Republicans on key committees |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |work=Politico |date=February 11, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n===2013 federal government shutdown===\nMeadows has been described as playing an important part of the [[United States federal government shutdown of 2013]].<ref name=\"architect\">{{cite news |last=Caldwell |first= Leigh Ann |title= Architect of the brink: Meet the man behind the government shutdown |url= http://www.cnn.com/2013/09/27/politics/house-tea-party/index.html |accessdate= October 8, 2013 |newspaper= CNN |date= October 1, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"constituents\">{{cite news |last=Ostendorff |first=John |title= Meadows says constituents back his shutdown fight |url= http://www.citizen-times.com/article/20131003/NEWS/310030079/Meadows-says-constituents-back-his-shutdown-fight |accessdate= October 8, 2013 |newspaper= Asheville Citizen-Times |date=October 3, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"road\">{{cite news |last=Straw |first= Joseph |title=Tea Party-backed Rep. Mark Meadows put government on road to shutdown |url= http://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/meadows-put-government-road-shutdown-article-1.1472233 |newspaper= New York Daily News |date= September 30, 2013 |accessdate= October 8, 2013}}</ref> On August 21, 2013, he wrote an [[open letter]] to Boehner and Majority Leader [[Eric Cantor]] encouraging them to \"affirmatively de-fund the implementation and enforcement of Obamacare in any relevant appropriations bills brought to the House floor in the 113th Congress, including any continuing appropriations bill.\"<ref name=\"auto8\">{{cite web |last=Meadows |first=Mark |title=Letter to Boehner and Cantor |url=http://meadows.house.gov/uploads/Meadows_DefundLetter.pdf |publisher=Meadows.house.gov |accessdate=October 8, 2013 |date=August 21, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131006003805/http://meadows.house.gov/uploads/Meadows_DefundLetter.pdf |archivedate=October 6, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"encouraging\">{{cite news |title= U.S. Rep. Mark Meadows Sends Letter to Boehner, Cantor Encouraging House Leadership to Defund Obamacare |url= http://www.hcpress.com/politics/u-s-rep-mark-meadows-sends-letter-to-boehner-cantor-encouraging-house-leadership-to-defund-obamacare.html |accessdate= October 8, 2013 |newspaper= High County Press |date= August 22, 2013 }}</ref> The document was signed by 79 of Meadows's colleagues in the House.<ref name=architect/><ref name=encouraging/> [[Heritage Action]] (which opened operations in North Carolina in January 2011<ref name=\"heritage\">{{cite news |title= Heritage Foundation sinks its roots in N.C. |author= Rob Christensen |url= http://www.newsobserver.com/2011/01/11/912355/heritage-foundation-sinks-its.html |work=[[The News & Observer]] |date=January 11, 2011 |accessdate= October 11, 2013 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131014125909/http://www.newsobserver.com/2011/01/11/912355/heritage-foundation-sinks-its.html |archivedate= October 14, 2013 }}</ref>), ran critical Internet advertisements in the districts of 100 Republican lawmakers who failed to sign the letter.<ref name=\"Stolberg2013\">{{cite news |last= Stolberg |first=Sheryl Gay |last2= McIntyre |first2=Mike |title=A federal budget crisis months in the planning |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/06/us/a-federal-budget-crisis-months-in-the-planning.html|newspaper=The New York Times |date= October 5, 2013 |accessdate= October 11, 2013}}</ref> The letter has been described as controversial within the Republican Party.<ref name=architect/><ref name=\"missive\">{{cite news |last=Omarzu |first=Tim |title= The letter behind the shutdown; GOP missive urges defunding of Obamacare |url= http://timesfreepress.com/news/2013/oct/04/the-letter-behind-the-shutdown/ |accessdate= October 8, 2013 |newspaper= Times Free Press |date= October 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Daily News (New York)|New York Daily News]]'' said Meadows put the federal government on the road to shutdown, saying calls to defund Obamacare through spending bills languished until Meadows wrote his letter.<ref name=road/> Meadows downplayed his influence, saying \"I'm one of 435 members and a very small part of this.\"<ref name=road/> CNN described Meadows as the \"architect of the brink\" for his letter suggesting that Obamacare be defunded in any continuing appropriations bill.<ref name=architect/> Meadows said that sensationalized his role.<ref name=constituents/>\n\nJohn Ostendorff of the ''Asheville Citizen-Times'' wrote that Meadows \"said it's best to close the government in the short term to win a delay on 'Obamacare', despite the potential negative impact on the economy.\"<ref name=constituents/> Ostendorff wrote that Meadows said he was doing what [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]] members in [[Western North Carolina]] wanted him to do.<ref name=constituents/> Meadows said his constituents wanted him to fight against Obamacare \"regardless of consequences.\"<ref name=architect/> Jane Bilello, head of the [[Asheville, North Carolina|Asheville]] Tea Party, said Meadows \"truly represents us\" on the issue of Obamacare.<ref name=architect/> Meadows reportedly holds conference calls with members of the Asheville Tea Party, telling them what's going on in Congress and about challenges he faces promoting their agenda.<ref name=architect/>\n\nIn public comments, Meadows said he was working on a compromise that involved passing appropriations bills that would fund only parts of the government, such as a [[October 2013 mini-continuing resolutions|bill]] to fund the National Park Service, [[Smithsonian Institution]], [[National Gallery of Art]], and [[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum]], and a [[October 2013 mini-continuing resolutions|bill]] to fund the [[National Institutes of Health]]. But partial or \"mini\" funding bills were rejected by the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] majority in the [[United States Senate]].<ref name=constituents/>\n\n===Resolution to remove Speaker Boehner===\nOn July 28, 2015, Meadows filed a resolution<ref name=\"resolution\">{{cite web |url= http://i2.cdn.turner.com/cnn/2015/images/07/28/meadows.hres.385.pdf |title= Resolution Declaring the office of Speaker of the House vacant |first= Mark |last= Meadows |date= July 28, 2015 |accessdate= July 29, 2015 }}</ref> to vote on removing [[John Boehner]] as [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|speaker of the House]].<ref name=\"tries\">{{cite news |title= Mark Meadows Tries to Boot Boehner From Speakership |work= National Journal |date= July 29, 2015 |accessdate= July 29, 2015 |first= Daniel |last= Neewhauser |url= http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress/mark-meadows-tries-to-boot-boehner-from-speakership-20150728 }}</ref> If the resolution passed, the House would then vote to elect a new speaker.<ref name= tries/>\n\nBecause Meadows filed it as a nonprivileged resolution, it was sent to the [[United States House Committee on Rules|House Committee on Rules]] for a vote first, rather than the House floor.<ref name= tries/> The Committee on Rules was considered to have many members who were loyal to Boehner, so the resolution was seen as unlikely to move forward.<ref name= tries/>\n\nMeadows said he filed the resolution because Boehner had \"endeavored to consolidate power, bypassing the majority\" of Congress; \"through inaction, caused the power of Congress to atrophy,\" \"uses the power of the office to punish Members who vote according to their conscience\"; \"has intentionally provided for voice votes on consequential and controversial legislation to be taken without notice and with few Members present\"; \"uses the legislative calendar to create crises for the American People\"; allowed members less than three days to review legislation before voting; and limited meaningful debate on the House floor.<ref name= resolution/> The resolution received support from Congressman [[Walter B. Jones Jr.]]<ref name=\"oustingboehner\">{{cite news|last1=Bresnahan|first1=John|title=John Boehner: Bid to boot him 'no big deal'|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2015/07/gop-leaders-ignore-attempt-john-boehner-ouster-120771.html|accessdate=July 29, 2015|publisher=Politico|date=July 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\nBoehner responded, \"Listen, you have a member here and a member there who are off the reservation. No big deal ... Listen, this is one member. All right. I've got broad support amongst my colleagues. And frankly, it isn't even deserving of a vote.\"<ref name=\"ousting\">{{cite news|last1=Fox|first1=Lauren|title=John Boehner's Not Giving Mark Meadows the Chance to Oust Him|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/congress/john-boehner-s-not-giving-meadows-the-chance-to-oust-him-20150729|accessdate=July 29, 2015|publisher=National Journal|date=July 29, 2015}}</ref> On September 25, 2015, Boehner announced his intention to resign as speaker.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2015/09/25/john-boehner-resigns-house-speaker/72793398/|title=Amid revolt, Boehner steps aside to avoid 'irreparable harm' to Congress|last=Shesgreen|first=Deirdre|date=September 26, 2015|work=USA Today|access-date=August 23, 2016|via=}}</ref> He officially resigned on October 31, 2015.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.cleveland.com/open/index.ssf/2015/10/john_boehner_exits_john_kasich.html|title=John Boehner exits, John Kasich books Stephen Colbert: Ohio Politics Roundup|last=Gomez|first=Harry|date=October 30, 2015|work=cleveland.com|access-date=August 23, 2016|via=}}</ref>\n\n===Controversies over chief of staff, education, and sexual harassment===\n\nA group of employees reported to Meadows's deputy chief of staff in October 2014 that they were uncomfortable with Meadows's then chief of staff, Kenny West, calling his behavior \"inappropriate towards them\". Meadows asked Representative [[Trey Gowdy]]'s chief of staff to interview the employees, and Meadows eventually limited or prohibited West's presence in Meadows's offices.<ref name=\"controversy\">{{cite news|last1=Troyan|first1=Mary|title=Ethics probe of Rep. Mark Meadows continues|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2016/08/17/ethics-probe-rep-mark-meadows-continues/88903504/|access-date=January 24, 2018|publisher=USA Today|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAlthough West resigned after the employees accused him of inappropriate behavior, he remained on the House payroll in violation of House rules, according to an independent House Ethics Committee investigation. Meadows paid West $58,125 from April 2015 to August 2015 even though he was no longer working in Meadows's office. There is \"substantial reason to believe that Representative Meadows retained an employee who did not perform duties commensurate with the compensation the employee received and certified that the compensation met applicable House standards, in violation of House rules and standards of conduct,\" the [[Office of Congressional Ethics]] report said.\n\nPrior to December 2018, Meadows claimed to have received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree.<ref name=Contorno/>  When questions about his credentials arose during media speculation that he was under consideration to serve as White House chief of staff, Meadows amended his official House biography and other sources to indicate that his degree was an associate, not a bachelor's.<ref name=Contorno/>\n\nIn November 2018 the House Ethics Committee fined Meadows over $40,000 after concluding he \"did not do enough to address\" sexual harassment allegations against West. The committee concluded Meadows took \"immediate and appropriate steps\" by separating West from female staffers and requesting an investigation, but noted that West retained his title and \"apparent authority over staff\" during this period. \"Representative Meadows could have and should have done more to ensure that his congressional office was free from discrimination or the perception of discrimination,\" the committee wrote. The committee fined Meadows $40,625 \"for Mr. West's salary that was not commensurate with his work.\" ''The Daily Beast'' previously reported that a former aide told the committee Meadows and other top staff members in his office were aware of West's behavior before it was publicly reported.<ref name=\"ongoingcontroversy\">{{cite news|last1=Stein|first1=Sam|title=Ex-Mark Meadows Aide Says Sexual Harassment in Congressman's Office Was Known Earlier Than Reported|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/ex-mark-meadows-aide-says-sexual-harassment-in-congressmans-office-was-known-earlier-than-reported|accessdate=January 24, 2018|publisher=The Daily Beast}}</ref>\n\n'''Committee assignments'''\n\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Africa, Global Health, Global Human Rights and International Organizations|Subcommittee on Africa, Global Health, Global Human Rights and International Organizations]]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on the Middle East and North Africa|Subcommittee on the Middle East and North Africa]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Committee on Oversight and Government Reform]]'''\n**  [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Government Operations|Subcommittee on Government Operations]] (Chairman)<ref>[https://meadows.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=54 Meadows named chair of Subcommittee on Government Operations], January 24, 2017</ref>\n** [[United States House Oversight Subcommittee on Economic Growth, Job Creation and Regulatory Affairs|Subcommittee on Economic Growth, Job Creation and Regulatory Affairs]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]]'''\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Aviation|Subcommittee on Aviation]]\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Economic Development, Public Buildings and Emergency Management|Subcommittee on Economic Development, Public Buildings and Emergency Management]]\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment|Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment]]\n\n'''Caucus memberships'''\n\n* [[Congressional Western Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://westerncaucus.house.gov/about/membership.htm|format=|publisher=Congressional Western Caucus|date=|accessdate=July 18, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[U.S.-Japan Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://usjapancaucus-castro.house.gov/members|format=| publisher=U.S. - Japan Caucus|date=|accessdate=December 14, 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Freedom Caucus|House Freedom Caucus]]\n*[[Second Amendment Caucus]]\n\n===Elections===\n\n====2012====\n{{See also|2012 United States House of Representatives elections in North Carolina#District 11}}\nIn late 2011 Meadows announced he was running for Congress in North Carolina's 11th congressional district, for the seat being vacated by [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] incumbent [[Heath Shuler]]. The district had been significantly altered in [[gerrymandering|redistricting]]. New lines were drawn straight through the middle of Warren Wilson College. Notably, it lost most of [[Asheville, North Carolina|Asheville]] to the [[North Carolina's 10th congressional district|10th district]], while picking up some heavily Republican territory in the foothills. The old 11th had a slight Republican lean, but the new 11th was on paper the most Republican district in the state.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2017/11/15/gerrymandering-5k-asheville-north-carolina-215829|title=I Ran the Worst 5K of My Life So I Could Explain Gerrymandering to You|last=Markovich|first=Jeremy|date=15 November 2017|website=Politico|access-date=23 March 2019}}</ref> In 2011 the North Carolina state legislature redrew the congressional districts based on updated population information from the 2010 census.<ref name=\"redistricting\"/> As a result the district is now 91.2% White, 3.0% Black, 1.4% Native American and 1.0% Asian.<ref name=\"redistricting\">{{cite web|url=http://ballotpedia.org/wiki/index.php/North_Carolina's_11th_congressional_district|title=North Carolina's 11th Congressional District - Ballotpedia|author=|date=|website=ballotpedia.org}}</ref> District 11 now includes Buncombe (Asheville), Clay, Cherokee, Graham, Haywood (Waynesville), Henderson (Hendersonville), Jackson (Sylva), Macon (Franklin), McDowell (Marion), Madison, Polk, Swain, Transylvania (Brevard) and Yancey (Burnsville) counties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ballotpedia.org/wiki/images/c/c2/NC11.jpg|title=NC11 Map|author=|date=|website=ballotpedia.org}}</ref><ref group=\"Notes\">District 10, with three counties, (Burke (Morganton), Mitchell and Rutherford) that border on District 11, also includes the counties of Avery, Caldwell, Catawba (Hickory and Newton), Cleveland (Shelby), Gaston (Gastonia) and Lincoln (Lincolnton).</ref>\n\nMeadows won the July 2012 Republican primary runoff,<ref>{{cite news|title=Mark Meadows sweeps 11th congressional GOP run-off|url=http://www.maconnews.com/news/state--region/3317-mark-meadows-sweeps-11th-congressional-gop-run-off|accessdate=August 31, 2012|newspaper=The Macon County News|date=July 19, 2012|author=Parker, Brittney|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021014858/http://www.maconnews.com/news/state--region/3317-mark-meadows-sweeps-11th-congressional-gop-run-off|archivedate=October 21, 2013}}</ref> and in the November general election faced Democratic nominee Hayden Rogers, who had been Shuler's chief of staff. On August 28 Meadows spoke at the [[2012 Republican National Convention]] in Tampa.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hendersonvillelightning.com/blog/2012/uncategorized/meadows-back-on-with-tuesday-slot-at-convention/ |title=Meadows back on with Tuesday slot at convention |newspaper=Henderson Lightning |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014123759/http://www.hendersonvillelightning.com/blog/2012/uncategorized/meadows-back-on-with-tuesday-slot-at-convention/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 14, 2013 |date=August 27, 2012 |department=Mossblog |access-date=March 25, 2017 }}</ref> He won the general election with approximately 57% of the vote<ref>{{cite web|url=http://results.enr.clarityelections.com/NC/42923/114047/Web01/en/summary.html|title=NC State Board of Elections|author=|date=|website=clarityelections.com}}</ref> and took office in January 2013.\n\n====2014====\n{{See also|2014 United States House of Representatives elections in North Carolina#District 11}}\nMeadows was reelected with 62.9% of the vote.\n\n====2016====\n{{See also|2016 United States House of Representatives elections in North Carolina#District 11}}\nMeadows appeared with candidate [[Donald Trump]] on the campaign trail in Winston-Salem, North Carolina in July 2016 just after the Republican National Convention, leading the crowd in a chant, \"Lock her up\", an anti-Hillary Clinton refrain.<ref>{{cite news |first=Jenna |last=Johnson |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/07/26/at-donald-trumps-north-carolina-rally-the-warm-up-acts-nearly-upstaged-the-nominee/ |department=Post Politics |title=At Donald Trump's North Carolina rally, the warm-up acts nearly upstaged the nominee |date=July 26, 2016 |newspaper=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nMeadows won re-election with 64.1% of the vote.\n\n====2018====\n[[File:Mark Meadows (39818366944).jpg|right|thumb|Mark Meadows at 2018 [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] (CPAC) in [[National Harbor, Maryland]]]]\n{{See also|2018 United States House of Representatives elections in North Carolina#District 11}}\nMeadows won reelection to his seat in the November 6, 2018 election, receiving 59% of the vote to his Democratic opponent Phillip Price's 38%.<ref>{{Cite web|title=North Carolina's 11th Congressional District election, 2018|url=https://ballotpedia.org/North_Carolina%27s_11th_Congressional_District_election,_2018|website=ballotpedia.org}}</ref>\n\nDuring the campaign Meadows supported President Trump\u2019s agenda, calling him a \"conservative president\" in 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/mark-meadows-donald-trump-is-a-conservative|title=Mark Meadows: 'Donald Trump is a conservative'|date=2017-03-31|website=Washington Examiner|language=en|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref> and suggesting that Republicans who didn't support Trump should be removed from office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/house/355311-meadows-time-to-eject-lawmakers-who-dont-back-trump|title=Meadows: Time to 'eject' lawmakers who don't back Trump|last=Rowland|first=Geoffrey|date=2017-10-13|website=TheHill|language=en|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref> Trump\u2019s son-in-law [[Jared Kushner]] attended a private fundraiser for Meadows.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/09/01/kushner-fundraises-for-mark-meadows-242244|title=Kushner fundraises for Mark Meadows|website=[[Politico]]|date=2017-09-01}}</ref> In January 2018 Meadows traveled to [[Davos]], Switzerland, with a congressional delegation for the World Economic Forum, along with a White House delegation including Trump and cabinet members including Treasury Secretary [[Steven Mnuchin]], Secretary of State [[Rex Tillerson]], and Energy Secretary [[Rick Perry]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/government-shutdown-deal-saves-congressional-trip-to-davos-2018-1|title=The deal to end the government shutdown saved the congressional trip to an elite gathering in Davos, Switzerland|last=Perticone|first=Joe|date=January 22, 2018|accessdate=January 23, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180124083332/http://www.businessinsider.com/government-shutdown-deal-saves-congressional-trip-to-davos-2018-1|archivedate=January 24, 2018 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.citizen-times.com/story/news/politics/elections/2018/01/26/meadows-attends-economic-forum-davos-switzerland-speaks-panel/1070763001/|title=Mark Meadows attends economic forum in Switzerland, speaks on panel|last=Barrett|first=Mark|date=January 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2020====\n\nOn December 19, 2019, Meadows announced that he would not seek reelection [[2020 United States House of Representatives elections in North Carolina#District 11|in 2020]].<ref name=\"won't run\">{{cite news |last=McPherson |first=Lindsey |date=December 29, 2019 |title=North Carolina's Mark Meadows won't run for reelection |url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/congress/north-carolinas-mark-meadows-wont-run-reelection |work=[[Roll Call]] |location=[[Washington, D.C.]] |access-date=December 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==White House chief of staff==\nIn December 2018, Meadows was vocal about his desire to work in the White House as [[White House Chief of Staff|chief of staff]] upon the January 2019 departure of [[John F. Kelly]].<ref>Caralle, Katelyn. (December 10, 2018). \"Mark Meadows wants to be Trump's chief of staff.\" [https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/news/white-house/mark-meadows-wants-to-be-trumps-chief-of-staff Washington Examiner website] Retrieved December 10, 2018.</ref>\n\nOn March 6, 2020, Trump named Meadows the next White House chief of staff,<ref>{{cite tweet |number=1236096307103707136 |title=I am pleased to announce that Congressman Mark Meadows will become White House Chief of Staff |date=March 6, 2020 |access-date=March 6, 2020 |first=Donald J. |last=Trump |author-link=Donald Trump |user=realDonaldTrump |language=en}}</ref> succeeding acting chief of staff [[Mick Mulvaney]].<ref>{{Cite news |last=Baker |first=Peter |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/06/us/politics/trump-mark-meadows-mick-mulvaney.html |title=Trump Names Mark Meadows Chief of Staff, Ousting Mick Mulvaney |date=March 6, 2020 |work=The New York Times |access-date=March 6, 2020 |url-status=live |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=Zeke |last2=Colvin |first2=Jill |last3=Taylor |first3=Andrew |title=Meadows toggles between legislator, White House roles |url=https://apnews.com/b99ed04440019680c785a897df91548a |date=March 27, 2020 |work=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> Meadows resigned from the House on March 30, 2020,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lesniewski |first1=Niels |last2=McPherson |first2=Lindsey |title=Rep. Mark Meadows resigns to become White House chief of staff |url=https://www.rollcall.com/2020/03/30/rep-mark-meadows-resigns-to-become-white-house-chief-of-staff/ |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=[[Roll Call]] |date=March 30, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> and began his new role the next day. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/politics-news/rep-mark-meadows-resigns-congress-take-chief-staff-role-n1172621|title=Rep. Mark Meadows resigns from Congress to become Trump's chief of staff|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n== Political positions ==\n\n=== Abortion ===\nMeadows is [[pro-life]] and has called [[Abortion in the United States|abortion]] a tragedy. He opposes federal funding for abortion and believes parents should be notified of underage abortion procedures. He also opposes churches and other religious sites being forced to provide [[birth control]] options.<ref name=\"issues\"/>\n\n=== Birtherism ===\nWhile running for office in June 2012, Meadows said, \"2012 is the time we are going to send Mr. Obama home to Kenya or wherever it is,\" implying that President Obama was [[Barack Obama citizenship conspiracy theories|not born in the United States]]. He made a similar comment later that month. When asked about his comment, Meadows said it was \"a non-issue\", \"probably a poor choice of words on my part\" and that he ultimately believed that Obama was an American citizen.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.rollcall.com/news/politics/north-carolina-candidate-appears-to-flirt-with-birtherism|title=North Carolina: Candidate Appears to Flirt With Birtherism|last=Miller|first=Joshua|date=2012-06-26|access-date=2019-02-28|last2=Miller|first2=Joshua|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Budget ===\nMeadows is part of a group that has advocated for a [[balanced budget amendment]] to the United States Constitution. He opposed the recent federal stimulus spending and has expressed a desire for the federal spending growth rate to be capped at the inflation rate. He supports a moratorium on all earmarks until the budget has been balanced. Meadows opposes any cuts to military spending levels.<ref name=\"issues\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/NC/Mark_Meadows.htm|title=Mark Meadows : (Republican, district 11)|work=On the Issues}}</ref>\n\n=== Civil rights ===\nIn February 2013 Meadows voted against renewing the [[Violence Against Women Act]]. Meadows has said he casts his votes based not on his personal feelings but on what the majority of his constituents in \"God's Country\" tell him to do.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/nation/2013/06/22/new-district-maps-reaped-rewards-for-gop-congress-but-cost-fewer-moderates-more-gridlock/B6jCugm94tpBvVu77ay0wJ/story.html|title=Turning the political map into a partisan weapon|last=Jan|first=Tracy|date=June 23, 2013|work=The Boston Globe|access-date=January 24, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n=== Environment and energy ===\nIn December 2016 Meadows gave Trump a wish list of regulations to be repealed. It included a demand to get rid of federal funding to study climate change. He also requested Trump repeal several environmental regulations, including the [[Renewable Fuel Standard (United States)|Renewable Fuel Standard]], end the prohibition of drilling oil on federal lands, and pull the US out of the [[Paris Agreement|Paris Climate Agreement]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/12/15/house-conservatives-want-trump-to-undo-regulations-on-fda-climate-uber/|title=House conservatives want Trump to undo regulations on climate, FDA, Uber|website=The Washington Post|access-date=May 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nMeadows has said that [[cap-and-trade]] emission policies are ineffective and have minimal impact on the global environment. He has proposed that the United States tap into oil and gas reserves to keep energy prices low and develop [[United States energy independence|energy independence]]. He supports tapping into off-shore oil and gas supplies.<ref name=\"issues\"/>\n\n=== LGBT rights ===\nMeadows opposes [[same-sex marriage]]. In March 2013, he said that if the Supreme Court allowed gay marriage, it would cause a constitutional crisis if the federal government decided to dismiss state decisions and thus infringe on state's rights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontopmag.com/article.aspx?id=14815&MediaType=1&Category=26|title=Rep. Mark Meadows Warns Of 'Constitutional Crisis' If SCOTUS Rules For Gay Marriage|date=Mar 29, 2013|work=On Top}}</ref>\n\n=== Gun control ===\nMeadows opposes any [[Gun control in the United States|restrictions on gun purchases]] and opposes a national gun registry that would list detailed information about firearm ownership.<ref name=\"issues\"/>\n\n=== Healthcare ===\nMeadows opposes the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] (Obamacare), and has stated that it should be replaced by private enterprise.<ref name=\"issues\"/>\n\nLess than a year after taking office, Meadows wrote the letter that initially urged House Speaker [[John Boehner]] to shut down the government unless the ACA was defunded. Some constituents have criticized him as responsible for the 2013 government shutdown; ''[[The Washington Post]]'' called him its \"chief architect\". His district lost up to $1 million per day during the shutdown because the national parks were closed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/rep-mark-meadows-pushed-for-a-shutdown-what-did-it-bring-his-NC-district-frustration/2013/10/19/d8a1dcf2-380c-11e3-8a0e-4e2cf80831fc_story.html|title=Rep. Mark Meadows pushed for a shutdown. What did it bring his N.C. district? Frustration.|website=The Washington Post|access-date=May 26, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Meadows voted for a budget resolution that initiated the process of repealing Obamacare.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.healthreformvotes.org/congress/roll-call-votes/h58-115.2017|title=HR 3: A budget resolution to begin the process of repealing the ACA.|work=HealthReformVotes.org|access-date=May 25, 2017|language=en}}</ref> On May 4, 2017, Meadows voted for the [[American Health Care Act of 2017|American Health Care Act]] (AHCA), which would partially repeal and replace Obamacare.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/05/04/us/politics/house-vote-republican-health-care-bill.html|title=How Every Member Voted on the House Health Care Bill|last=Shorey|first=Gregor Aisch, Sarah Almukhtar, Wilson Andrews, Jeremy Bowers, Nate Cohn, K. k Rebecca Lai, Jasmine C. Lee, Alicia Parlapiano, Adam Pearce, Nadja Popovich, Kevin Quealy, Rachel|date=May 4, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=May 25, 2017|last2=Singhvi|first2=Anjali|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nAfter the [[Congressional Budget Office]] (CBO) released numbers about the AHCA's effects on Americans on May 24, 2017, there were several reports that Meadows became emotional after reading about the AHCA's likely effects on those with preexisting conditions.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aol.com/article/news/2017/05/25/gop-rep-mark-meadows-reportedly-teared-up-after-reading-analysis-obamacare-replacement-bill-pre-existing-conditions/22109412/|title=GOP Rep. Mark Meadows reportedly teared up after reading Obamacare replacement bill analysis|last=Staff|first=AOL|work=AOL.com|access-date=May 25, 2017|language=en}}</ref> Others reported he cried only after bringing up his family members who had dealt with preexisting conditions, including his sister who had died of breast cancer, and his father who had died of lung cancer. Meadows said he wouldn't \"make a political decision today that affects somebody's sister or father because I wouldn't do it to myself.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.charlotteobserver.com/news/politics-government/article152692439.html|title=No, an NC congressman didn't cry about the health bill score|work=charlotteobserver|access-date=May 25, 2017|language=en}}</ref> When asked about the CBO numbers, Meadows said the government should ensure people with preexisting conditions can afford health care, saying, \"The president is committed to making sure preexisting conditions are covered in principle and in practice, which means that funding has to be there to make it work.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/meadows-floats-more-funding-for-repeal-bill-after-cbo-score/article/2624096|title=Meadows floats more funding for repeal bill after CBO score|last=King|first=Robert|work=Washington Examiner|access-date=May 25, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Net neutrality ===\nMeadows opposes regulations that require all internet providers provide [[Net neutrality in the United States|internet at equal speeds to all parties]]. In 2016 he gave Trump a list of regulations to repeal that included net neutrality regulations by the [[Federal Communications Commission]].<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n=== Russia investigation ===\nMeadows, a member of the [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Reform|House Oversight and Government Reform Committee]], has been a harsh critic of Special Counsel Robert Mueller's [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u2013present)|investigation into Russian interference in the 2016 election]]. During Trump's presidency, Meadows regularly conferred with Trump about Mueller's probe.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/05/16/trump-mueller-russia-probe-doj-documents-592148|title=GOP lawmakers to Trump: Make DOJ release Mueller documents|work=POLITICO|access-date=May 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/bigger-than-watergate-trump-joins-push-by-allies-to-expose-an-fbi-source/2018/05/17/db211542-59ea-11e8-8836-a4a123c359ab_story.html|title='Bigger than Watergate': Trump joins push by allies to expose role of an FBI source|last=Rucker|first=Philip|date=May 17, 2018|work=The Washington Post|access-date=May 18, 2018|last2=Costa|first2=Robert|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286|last3=Leonnig|first3=Carol D.|last4=Dawsey|first4=Josh}}</ref> Meadows has been described as a \"Trump ally\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/406008-trump-blasts-fbi-doj-over-strzok-page-media-leak-strategy|title=Trump blasts FBI, DOJ over Strzok-Page 'Media Leak Strategy'|last=Birnbaum|first=Emily|date=September 11, 2018|work=TheHill|access-date=September 11, 2018|language=en}}</ref> In May 2018, Meadows called for a financial audit of the Mueller investigation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/387163-freedom-caucus-chairman-wants-financial-audit-of-mueller-investigation|title=Freedom Caucus chairman wants financial audit of Mueller investigation|last=Delk|first=Josh|date=May 10, 2018|work=TheHill|access-date=May 18, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2018, along with [[Jim Jordan (American politician)|Jim Jordan]], Meadows called on the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] to \"review allegations that Deputy Attorney General [[Rod Rosenstein]] threatened to subpoena phone records and documents from a House Intelligence Committee staffer\". An aide termed the deputy AG's threats \"downright chilling\". In their written request, they wrote that in his use of investigative powers, Rosenstein retaliated \"against rank-and-file staff members\", therefore abusing his authority.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Brufke |first1=Julie Grace |title=Freedom Caucus lawmakers call on DOJ to probe Rosenstein allegations |url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/397340-freedom-caucus-lawmakers-call-on-doj-to-probe-rosenstein-allegations |website=The Hill |accessdate=July 17, 2018}}</ref> Furthermore, during a ''[[Fox News]]'' interview by [[Laura Ingraham]] that same month, he \"threatened to force a vote on the GOP resolution\" that would impeach the deputy AG. Arguing he could force the resolution to the floor as a \"[[Raise a question of privilege|privileged motion]]\", he elaborated: \"we hope it doesn't have to come to that\". He filed articles of impeachment against Rosenstein on July 25, although the measure cannot be \"brought straight to the House floor\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Birnbaum |first1=Emily |title=Meadows threatens to force a vote on Rosenstein impeachment |url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/398931-republican-threatens-to-force-a-vote-on-rosenstein-impeachment |website=The Hill |accessdate=July 27, 2018}}</ref> Meadows's Democratic opponent in the 2018 election, Phillip Price, condemned the impeachment resolution as an attempt to shut down the Justice Department's investigation of Russian meddling into the 2016 election through \"obstruction of justice.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Democrat rips Meadows' Rosenstein threat as 'obstruction of justice' |url=https://www.hendersonvillelightning.com/four-seasons-politics/7145-democrat-rips-meadows-justice-threat-as-obstruction-of-justice.html |newspaper=Hendersonville Lightning |location=[[Hendersonville, North Carolina]] |accessdate=August 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Taxes ===\nMeadows has signed the [[Taxpayer Protection Pledge]], and he opposes a raise in all taxes, including the income tax. Meadows supports a [[flat tax|flat-rate income tax]] for all earners and a repeal of the raise in the [[capital gains tax]]. He also supports the elimination of the [[Estate tax in the United States|estate tax]].<ref name=\"issues\"/>\n\n=== Trump\u2013Ukraine scandal ===\n{{Further|Trump\u2013Ukraine scandal}}\nOn December 8, 2019, Meadows claimed that Trump never asked a foreign leader to investigate a political rival,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.axios.com/mark-meadows-trump-ukraine-biden-c43d2e8d-785b-462f-9aa1-b03bc1fa24a5.html|title=\"He didn't do that\": Mark Meadows denies Trump asked Ukraine to investigate political rival|last=Bassou|first=Zachary|date=December 8, 2019|website=Axios|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=December 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2019/12/08/mark-meadows-trump-ukraine-investigate-rivals-078189|title=Mark Meadows claims Trump did not ask Ukraine to investigate rivals|last=Kullgren|first=Ian|date=2019-12-08|website=POLITICO|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref> despite a transcript of the July 25, 2019 phone call between Trump and Ukrainian President [[Volodymyr Zelensky]] that some interpreted to mean that Trump had asked Zelensky to investigate former Vice President [[Joe Biden]]<ref name=\":2\" /> and in spite of Trump's October 3, 2019 public calling upon [[China]] to investigate Hunter Biden's business activities there while his father was vice president.<ref name=\"Wagner\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-impeachment-whistleblower/2019/10/02/80df829a-e494-11e9-b403-f738899982d2_story.html|title=Live updates: Trump calls for China to investigate Bidens; former Ukraine envoy testifies on Capitol Hill|last1=Wagner|first1=John|date=October 3, 2019|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=December 8, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.is/us6JC|archive-date=October 2, 2019|last2=Sonmez|first2=Felicia|url-access=limited}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/oct/03/trump-biden-china-investigation-demand|title=Trump calls on China to investigate Biden in extraordinary demand|last=Borger|first=Julian|date=October 3, 2019|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=October 5, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191004142600/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/oct/03/trump-biden-china-investigation-demand|archive-date=December 8, 2019|last2=Gambino|first2=Lauren|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Meadows said he would be \"OK\" with a Democratic president doing what Trump did: \u201cWe have Democrat Senators who have done just that.\u201d<ref>{{Citation|title=Meadows: I'd be OK with a Dem doing what Trump did - CNN Video|url=https://www.cnn.com/videos/politics/2019/12/08/sotu-meadows-dem.cnn|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref>\n\n=== Wages ===\nMeadows presented a letter to Trump in 2016 that demanded the repeal of the federal requirement that [[public works]] projects pay laborers and mechanics the locally prevailing wages, which was initially made to protect traveling black workers in the South from being paid far less than local workers. The letter also demanded the repeal of the overtime rule from the Obama administration, which said people making less than $47,000 a year must be paid extra for overtime hours, compared to the previous requirement that those making over $23,000 a year could be denied overtime pay if the worker's duties could be considered \"managerial.\" The letter also demanded the end of regulations requiring federal contractors to be paid for sick leave.<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|group=\"Notes\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/North_Carolina/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Mark_Meadows_%5BR-11%5D|Mark Meadows}}\n* {{C-SPAN|Mark Meadows}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=M001187 | votesmart=136459 | fec=H2NC11080 | congress=mark-meadows/2142}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=7684212|name=Mark Meadows}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DRjRNwgdyPE Mark Meadow's Commencement address at Patrick Henry College]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Heath Shuler]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from North Carolina|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[North Carolina's 11th congressional district]]|years=2013\u20132020}}\n{{s-vac}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jim Jordan (American politician)|Jim Jordan]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Ranking Member of the [[United States House Committee on Oversight and Reform|House Oversight Committee]]|years=2020}}\n{{s-aft|after=TBD}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|befor